# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gynaecology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Abortion continues to be a controversial subject in many societies on religious, moral, ethical, practical, and political grounds.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Though it has been banned and otherwise limited by law in many jurisdictions, abortions continue to be common in many areas, even where they are illegal.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] According to a 2007 study conducted by the Guttmacher Institute and the World Health Organization, abortion rates are similar in countries where the procedure is legal and in countries where it is not, due to unavailability of modern contraceptives in areas where abortion is illegal.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Also according to the study, the number of abortions worldwide is declining due to increased access to contraception.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Abortion has existed since ancient times, with natural abortifacients being found amongst a wide variety of tribal people and in most written sources.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] The earliest known records of abortion techniques and general reproductive regulation date as far back as 2700 BC in China, and 1550 BC in Egypt.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Early texts contain little mention of abortion or abortion law.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] When it does appear, it is entailed in concerns about male property rights, preservation of social order, and the duty to produce fit citizens for the state or community.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] The harshest penalties were generally reserved for a woman who procured an abortion against her husband's wishes, and for slaves who produced abortion in a woman of high status.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Religious texts often contained severe condemnations of abortion, recommending penance but seldom enforcing secular punishment.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] As a matter of common law in England and the United States, abortion was illegal anytime after quickening—when the movements of the fetus could first be felt by the woman.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Under the born alive rule, the fetus was not considered a "reasonable being" *in rerum natura*; and abortion was not treated as murder in English law.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] In the 19th century, many Western countries began to codify abortion laws or place further restrictions on the practice.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Anti-abortion movements were led by a combination of groups opposed to abortion on moral grounds, and by medical professionals who were concerned about the danger presented by the procedure and the regular involvement of non-medical personnel in performing abortions.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Nevertheless, it became clear that illegal abortions continued to take place in large numbers even where abortions were rigorously restricted.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] It was difficult to obtain sufficient evidence to prosecute the women and abortion doctors, and judges and juries were often reluctant to convict.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] For example, Henry Morgentaler, a Canadian pro-choice advocate, was never convicted by a jury.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] He was acquitted by a jury in the 1973 court case, but the acquittal was overturned by five judges on the Quebec Court of Appeal in 1974.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] He went to prison, appealed, and was again acquitted.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] In total, he served 10 months, suffering a heart attack while in solitary confinement.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Many were also outraged at the invasion of privacy and the medical problems resulting from abortions taking place illegally in medically dangerous circumstances.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Political movements soon coalesced around the legalization of abortion and liberalization of existing laws.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] By the first half of the 20th century, many countries had begun to liberalize abortion laws, at least when performed to protect the woman's life and in some cases on the woman's request.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Under Vladimir Lenin, the Soviet Union became the first modern state in legalizing abortions on request—the law was first introduced in the Russian SFSR in 1920, in the Ukrainian SSR in July 1921, and then in the whole country.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] The Bolsheviks saw abortion as a social evil created by the capitalist system, which left women without the economic means to raise children, forcing them to perform abortions.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] The Soviet state initially preserved the tsarist ban on abortion, which treated the practice as premeditated murder.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] However, abortion had been practiced by Russian women for decades and its incidence skyrocketed further as a result of the Russian Civil War, which had left the country economically devastated and made it extremely difficult for many people to have children.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] The Soviet state recognized that banning abortion would not stop the practice because women would continue using the services of private abortionists.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] In rural areas, these were often old women who had no medical training, which made their services very dangerous to women's health.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] In November 1920, the Soviet government legalized abortion in state hospitals.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] The state considered abortion as a temporary necessary evil, which would disappear in the future communist society, which would be able to provide for all the children conceived.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] In 1936, Joseph Stalin placed prohibitions on abortions, which restricted them to medically recommended cases only, in order to increase population growth after the enormous loss of life in World War I and the Russian Civil War.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] In the 1930s, several countries (Poland, Turkey, Denmark, Sweden, Iceland, Mexico) legalized abortion in some special cases (pregnancy from rape, threat to mother's health, fetal malformation).
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] In Japan, abortion was legalized in 1948 by the Eugenic Protection Law, amended in May 1949 to allow abortions for economic reasons.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Abortion was legalized in 1952 in Yugoslavia (on a limited basis), and again in 1955 in the Soviet Union on request.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Some Soviet allies (Poland, Hungary, Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia, Romania) legalized abortion in the late 1950s under pressure from the Soviets.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] In the United Kingdom, the Abortion Act of 1967 clarified and prescribed abortions as legal up to 28 weeks (later reduced to 24 weeks).
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Other countries soon followed, including Canada (1969), the United States (1973 in most states, pursuant to *Roe v.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Supreme Court decision which legalized abortion nationwide until 2022), Tunisia and Denmark (1973), Austria (1974), France and Sweden (1975), New Zealand (1977), Italy (1978), the Netherlands (1984), and Belgium (1990).
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] However, these countries vary greatly in the circumstances under which abortion was to be permitted.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] In 1975, the West German Supreme Court struck down a law legalizing abortion, holding that it contradicted the constitution's human rights guarantees.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] In 1976, a law was adopted which enabled abortions up to 12 weeks.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] The other schools hold intermediate positions. ...
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] The penalty prescribed for an illegal abortion varies according to particular circumstances involved.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] The table below lists in chronological order the United Nations member states that have legalized abortion on request in at least some initial part of the pregnancy, or that have fully decriminalized abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] As of 2025, 67 countries have legalized or decriminalized abortion on request.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Where a country has legalized abortion on request, prohibited it, and legalized it again (e.g., former Soviet Union, Romania), only the later year is included.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Countries that result from the merger of states where abortion on request was legal at the moment of unification show the year when it became legal across the whole national territory (e.g., Germany, Vietnam).
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Similarly, countries where not all subnational jurisdictions have legalized abortion on request are not included, leading to the exclusion of Australia, Mexico, and the United Kingdom.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Countries where abortion on request was once legalized nationwide but has since been prohibited in at least part of the country, such as the United States and Poland, are also excluded.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Countries are counted even if they were not yet independent at the time.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] The year refers to when the relevant law or judicial decision came into force, which may be different from the year when it was approved.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] There are no international or multinational treaties that deal directly with abortion but human rights law and international criminal law touch on the issues.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] The Nuremberg Military Tribunal decided the case of *United States v Greifelt and Others* (1948) on the basis that abortion was a crime within its jurisdiction according to the law defining crimes against humanity and thus within its definition of murder and extermination.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] The Catholic Church remains highly influential in Latin America, and opposes the legalisation of abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] The American Convention on Human Rights, which in 2013 had 23 Latin American parties, declares human life as commencing with conception.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] In Latin America, abortion on request is only legal in Cuba (1965), Uruguay (2012), Argentina (2021), Colombia (2022) and in parts of Mexico.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Abortions are completely banned in the Dominican Republic, El Salvador, Honduras and Nicaragua, and only allowed in certain restricted circumstances in most other Latin American nations.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] In the 2010 case of *A, B and C v Ireland*, the European Court of Human Rights found that the European Convention on Human Rights did not include a right to an abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] In the 2016 case of *Mellet v Ireland*, the UN HRC found Ireland's abortion laws violated the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights because Irish law banned abortion in cases of fatal fetal abnormalities.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] While abortions are legal at least under certain conditions in almost all countries, these conditions vary widely.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] According to a United Nations (UN) report with data gathered up to 2019, abortion is allowed in 98% of countries in order to save a woman's life.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Other commonly accepted reasons are preserving physical (72%) or mental health (69%), in cases of rape or incest (61%), and in cases of fetal impairment (61%).
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Performing an abortion because of economic or social reasons is accepted in 37% of countries.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Performing abortion only on the basis of a woman's request is allowed in 34% of countries, including in Canada, most European countries and China.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] The exact scope of each legal ground also varies.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] For example, the laws of some countries cite health risks and fetal impairment as general grounds for abortion and allow a broad interpretation of such terms in practice, while other countries restrict them to a specific list of medical conditions or subcategories.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Many countries that allow abortion have gestational limits for the procedure depending on the reason; with the majority being up to 12 weeks for abortion on request, up to 24 weeks for social, economic, rape, or incest reasons, and more for fetal impairment or threats to the woman's health or life.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] In some countries, additional procedures must be followed before the abortion can be carried out even if the basic grounds for it are met.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] How strictly all of the procedures dictated in the legislation are followed in practice is another matter.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] For example, in the United Kingdom, a Care Quality Commission's report in 2012 found that several NHS clinics were circumventing the law, using forms pre-signed by one doctor, thus allowing abortions to patients who only met with one doctor.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] The table below summarizes the legal grounds for abortion in all United Nations member states and United Nations General Assembly observer states and some countries with limited recognition.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] This table is mostly based on data compiled by the United Nations up to 2019, with some updates, additions and clarifications citing other sources.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] The table below summarizes the legal grounds for abortion in autonomous jurisdictions not included in the previous table.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Legal limits may not be directly comparable.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Limits may be expressed in trimesters, months, weeks of pregnancy (implantation), weeks from fertilization, or weeks from last menstrual period (LMP).
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] According to a report by Women on Waves, approximately 25% of the world's population lives in countries with "highly restrictive abortion laws"—that is, laws which either completely ban abortion, or allow it only to save the mother's life.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] This category includes several countries in Latin America, Africa, Asia and Oceania, as well as Andorra and Malta in Europe.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] El Salvador has some of the strictest abortion laws of any country.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Abortion under all circumstances, including rape, incest, and risk to the mother's health, is illegal.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Women can be criminalized and penalized to up to 40 years in prison after being found guilty of an abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] El Salvador's abortion laws are so severe that miscarriages and stillbirths can sometimes be enough for conviction.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] The Inter-American Court has already ruled that El Salvador was responsible for the death of Manuela, who was sentenced to 30 years in prison in 2008 for aggravated homicide after suffering an obstetric emergency that resulted in her losing her pregnancy.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Controversy over the beginning of pregnancy occurs in different contexts, particularly in a legal context, and is particularly discussed within the abortion debate from the point of measuring the gestational age of the pregnancy.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] Pregnancy can be measured from a number of convenient points, including the day of last menstruation, ovulation, fertilization, implantation and chemical detection.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p01] A common medical way to calculate gestational age is to measure pregnancy from the first day of the last menstrual cycle.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p02] Exceptions in abortion laws occur either in countries where abortion is as a general rule illegal or in countries that have abortion on request with gestational limits.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p02] For example, if a country allows abortion on request until 12 weeks, it may create exceptions to this general gestation limit for later abortions in specific circumstances.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p02] There are a few exceptions commonly found in abortion laws.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p02] Legal domains which do not have abortion on demand will often allow it when the health of the mother is at stake.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p02] Laws allowing abortion in cases of rape or incest often differ.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p02] Wade*, thirteen U.S. states allowed abortion in the case of either rape or incest, but only Mississippi permitted abortion of pregnancies due to rape, and no state permitted it for just incest.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p02] Many countries allow abortion only through the first or second trimester, and some may allow abortion in cases of fetal defects, e.g., Down syndrome, or where the pregnancy is the result of a sexual crime.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p02] Laws in some countries with liberal abortion laws protect access to abortion services.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p02] Such legislation often seeks to guard abortion clinics against obstruction, vandalism, picketing, and other actions, or to protect patients and employees of such facilities from threats and harassment.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p02] Other laws create a perimeter around a facility, known variously as a "buffer zone", "bubble zone", or "access zone", where demonstrations opposing abortion are not permitted.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p02] Protests and other displays are restricted to a certain distance from the building, which varies depending on the law.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p02] Similar zones have also been created to protect the homes of abortion providers and clinic staff.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p02] Bubble zone laws are divided into "fixed" and "floating" categories.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p02] Fixed bubble zone laws apply to the static area around the facility itself, and floating laws to objects in transit, such as people or cars.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p02] On 3 November 2020, an association of 20 Kenyan charities urged the government of Kenya to withdraw from the Geneva Consensus Declaration (GCD), a US-led international accord that sought to limit access to abortion for girls and women around the world.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-law-p02] GCD was signed by 33 nations, on 22 October 2020.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] When done legally in industrialized societies, induced abortion is one of the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Modern methods use medication or surgery for abortions.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The drug mifepristone (aka RU-486) in combination with prostaglandin appears to be as safe and effective as surgery during the first and second trimesters of pregnancy.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Self-managed medication abortion is highly effective and safe throughout the first trimester.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The most common surgical technique involves dilating the cervix and using a suction device.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Birth control, such as contraceptive pills or intrauterine devices, can be used immediately following an abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] When performed legally and safely on a woman who desires it, an induced abortion does not increase the risk of long-term mental or physical problems.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In contrast, unsafe abortions performed by unskilled individuals, with hazardous equipment, or in unsanitary facilities cause between 22,000 and 44,000 deaths and 6.9 million hospital admissions each year — responsible for between 5% and 13% of maternal deaths, especially in low-income countries.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization states that "access to legal, safe and comprehensive abortion care, including post-abortion care, is essential for the attainment of the highest possible level of sexual and reproductive health".
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Public health data show that making safe abortion legal and accessible reduces maternal deaths.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Around 73 million abortions are performed each year in the world, with about 45% done unsafely.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Abortion rates changed little between 2003 and 2008, before which they decreased for at least two decades as access to family planning and birth control increased.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] As of 2018, 37% of the world's women had access to legal abortions without limits as to reason.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Countries that permit abortions have different limits on how late in pregnancy abortion is allowed.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Abortion rates are similar between countries that restrict abortion and countries that broadly allow it, though this is partly because countries which restrict abortion tend to have higher unintended pregnancy rates.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Since 1973, there has been a global trend towards greater legal access to abortion, but there remains debate with regard to moral, religious, ethical, and legal issues.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Those who oppose abortion often argue that an embryo or fetus is a person with a right to life, and thus equate abortion with murder.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Those who support abortion's legality often argue that it is a woman's reproductive right.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Others favor legal and accessible abortion as a public health measure.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Abortion laws and views of the procedure are different around the world.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In some countries abortion is legal and women have the right to make the choice about abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In some areas, abortion is legal only in specific cases such as rape, incest, fetal defects, poverty, and risk to a woman's health.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Historically, abortions have been attempted using herbal medicines, sharp tools, forceful massage, or other traditional methods.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] An induced abortion is a medical procedure to end a pregnancy.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In present-day English, the term *abortion*, when used without further qualification, generally refers to induced abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] A pregnancy can be intentionally aborted in several ways.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The abortion method depends upon the gestational age of the embryo or fetus, which gains mass as the pregnancy progresses.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Abortion laws, regional availability, and the personal preference of the woman and her doctor may inform the woman's choice of a specific abortion procedure.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Abortions can be characterized as either therapeutic or elective.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] When an abortion is performed for medical reasons, the procedure is referred to as a therapeutic abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] An abortion is referred to as elective or voluntary when it is performed at the request of the woman for non-medical reasons.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Confusion sometimes arises over the term *elective* because "elective surgery" generally refers to all scheduled surgery, whether medically necessary or not.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] About one in five pregnancies worldwide ends with an induced abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Most abortions result from unintended pregnancies.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In the United Kingdom, 1 to 2% of abortions are done because of genetic problems in the fetus.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Miscarriage, also known as spontaneous abortion, is the unintentional expulsion of an embryo or fetus before the 24th week of gestation.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] A pregnancy that ends before 37 weeks of gestation resulting in a live-born infant is a "premature birth" or a "preterm birth".
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] When a fetus dies in utero after viability, or during delivery, it is usually termed "stillborn".
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Premature births and stillbirths are generally not considered to be miscarriages, although usage of these terms can sometimes overlap.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Studies of pregnant women in the US and China have shown that between 40% and 60% of embryos do not progress to birth.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The vast majority of miscarriages occur before the woman is aware that she is pregnant, and many pregnancies spontaneously abort before medical practitioners can detect an embryo.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Between 15% and 30% of known pregnancies end in clinically apparent miscarriage, depending upon the age and health of the pregnant woman.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] 80% of these spontaneous abortions happen in the first trimester.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The most common cause of spontaneous abortion during the first trimester is chromosomal abnormalities of the embryo or fetus, accounting for at least 50% of sampled early pregnancy losses.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Other causes include vascular disease (such as lupus), diabetes, other hormonal problems, infection, and abnormalities of the uterus.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Advancing maternal age and a woman's history of previous spontaneous abortions are the two leading factors associated with a greater risk of spontaneous abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] A spontaneous abortion can also be caused by accidental trauma; intentional trauma or stress to cause miscarriage is considered induced abortion or feticide.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] may determine which abortion methods are practiced.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Medical abortions are those induced by abortifacient pharmaceuticals.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Medical abortion became an alternative method of abortion with the availability of prostaglandin analogs in the 1970s and the antiprogestogen mifepristone (also known as RU-486) in the 1980s.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimens work faster and are more effective at later gestational ages than methotrexate–misoprostol combination regimens, and combination regimens are more effective than misoprostol alone, particularly in the second trimester.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Medical abortion regimens involving mifepristone followed by misoprostol in the cheek between 24 and 48 hours later are effective when performed before 70 days' gestation.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In very early abortions, up to 7 weeks gestation, medical abortion using a mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimen is considered to be more effective than surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration), especially when clinical practice does not include detailed inspection of aspirated tissue.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Early medical abortion regimens using mifepristone, followed 24–48 hours later by buccal or vaginal misoprostol are 98% effective up to 9 weeks gestational age; from 9 to 10 weeks efficacy decreases modestly to 94%.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] If medical abortion fails, surgical abortion must be used to complete the procedure.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Early medical abortions account for the majority of abortions before 9 weeks gestation in Britain, France, Switzerland, United States, and the Nordic countries.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] A 2020 Cochrane Systematic Review concluded that providing women with medications to take home to complete the second stage of the procedure for an early medical abortion results in an effective abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Further research is required to determine if self-administered medical abortion is as safe as provider-administered medical abortion, where a health care professional is present to help manage the medical abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Safely permitting women to self-administer abortion medication has the potential to improve access to abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The review also noted a research gap concerning methods to support women who take medication at home for a self-administered abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Up to 15 weeks' gestation, suction-aspiration or vacuum aspiration are the most common surgical methods of induced abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] *Manual vacuum aspiration* (MVA) consists of removing the fetus or embryo, placenta, and membranes by suction using a manual syringe, while *electric vacuum aspiration* (EVA) uses an electric pump.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Both techniques can be used very early in pregnancy.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] MVA can be used up to 14 weeks but is more often used earlier in the U.S.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] MVA, also known as "mini-suction" and "menstrual extraction", or EVA can be used in very early pregnancy when cervical dilation may not be required.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Dilation and curettage (D&C) refers to opening the cervix (dilation) and removing tissue (curettage) via suction or sharp instruments.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] D&C is a standard gynecological procedure performed for a variety of reasons, including examination of the uterine lining for possible malignancy, investigation of abnormal bleeding, and abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization recommends *sharp curettage* only when suction aspiration is unavailable.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Dilation and evacuation (D&E), used after 12 to 16 weeks, consists of opening the cervix and removing pregnancy tissue and fetal parts with suction and forceps.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] D&E is performed vaginally and does not require an incision.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Intact dilation and extraction (D&X) refers to a variant of D&E sometimes used after 18 to 20 weeks when removal of an intact fetus improves surgical safety or for other reasons.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Abortion may also be performed surgically by hysterotomy or gravid hysterectomy.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy abortion is a procedure similar to a caesarean section and is performed under general anesthesia.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] It requires a smaller incision than a caesarean section and can be used during later stages of pregnancy.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Gravid hysterectomy refers to removal of the whole uterus while still containing the pregnancy.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy and hysterectomy are associated with much higher rates of maternal morbidity and mortality than D&E or induction abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] First trimester procedures can generally be performed using local anesthesia, while second trimester methods may require deep sedation or general anesthesia.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In places lacking the necessary medical skill for dilation and extraction, or when preferred by practitioners, an abortion can be induced by first inducing labor and then inducing fetal demise if necessary.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] This is sometimes called "induced miscarriage".
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] This procedure may be performed from 13 weeks gestation to the third trimester.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Although it is very uncommon in the United States, more than 80% of induced abortions throughout the second trimester are labor-induced abortions in Sweden and other nearby countries.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Only limited data are available comparing labor-induced abortion with the dilation and extraction method.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Unlike D&E, labor-induced abortions after 18 weeks may be complicated by the occurrence of brief fetal survival, which may be legally characterized as live birth.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] For this reason, labor-induced abortion is legally risky in the United States.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Historically, a number of herbs reputed to possess abortifacient properties have been used in folk medicine.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Such herbs include tansy, pennyroyal, black cohosh, and the now-extinct silphium.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In 1978, one woman in Colorado died and another developed organ damage when they attempted to terminate their pregnancies by taking pennyroyal oil.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Because the indiscriminant use of herbs as abortifacients can cause serious—even lethal—side effects, such as multiple organ failure, such use is not recommended by physicians.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Abortion is sometimes attempted by causing trauma to the abdomen.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The degree of force, if severe, can cause serious internal injuries without necessarily succeeding in inducing miscarriage.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In Southeast Asia, there is an ancient tradition of attempting abortion through forceful abdominal massage.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] One of the bas reliefs decorating the temple of Angkor Wat in Cambodia depicts a demon performing such an abortion upon a woman who had been sent to the underworld.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Reported methods of unsafe, self-induced abortion include misuse of misoprostol and insertion of non-surgical implements such as knitting needles and clothes hangers into the uterus.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] These and other methods to terminate pregnancy may be called "induced miscarriage".
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Such methods are rarely used in countries where surgical abortion is legal and available.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The health risks of abortion depend principally on how, and under what conditions, the procedure is performed.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) defines unsafe abortions as a procedure for terminating an unintended pregnancy carried out either by persons lacking the necessary skills or in an environment that does not conform to minimal medical standards, or both.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Legal abortions performed in the developed world are among the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] According to a 2012 study in *Obstetrics & Gynecology*, in the United States the risk of maternal mortality is 14 times lower after induced abortion than after childbirth.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The CDC estimated in 2019 that US pregnancy-related mortality was 17.2 maternal deaths per 100,000 live births, while the US abortion mortality rate was 0.43 maternal deaths per 100,000 procedures.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In the UK, guidelines of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists state that "Women should be advised that abortion is generally safer than continuing a pregnancy to term." Worldwide, on average, abortion is safer than carrying a pregnancy to term.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In the US from 2000 to 2009, abortion had a mortality rate lower than plastic surgery, lower or similar to running a marathon, and about equivalent to traveling 760 miles (1,220 km) in a passenger car.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The risk of abortion-related mortality increases with gestational age, but remains lower than that of childbirth.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Outpatient abortion is as safe from 64 to 70 days' gestation as it before 63 days.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] A 2019 study indicated that five years after seeking abortion services, women who gave birth after being denied an abortion reported worse health than women who had either first or second trimester abortions.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] There is little difference in terms of safety and efficacy between medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol and surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration) in early first trimester abortions up to 10 weeks gestation.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Medical abortion using the prostaglandin analog misoprostol alone is less effective and more painful than medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol or surgical abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Vacuum aspiration in the first trimester is the safest method of surgical abortion, and can be performed in a primary care office, abortion clinic, or hospital.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Complications, which are rare, can include uterine perforation, pelvic infection, and retained products of conception requiring a second procedure to evacuate.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Infections account for one-third of abortion-related deaths in the United States.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The rate of complications of vacuum aspiration abortion in the first trimester is similar regardless of whether the procedure is performed in a hospital, surgical center, or office.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Preventive antibiotics (such as doxycycline or metronidazole) are typically given before abortion procedures, as they are believed to substantially reduce the risk of postoperative uterine infection; however, antibiotics are not routinely given with abortion pills.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The rate of failed procedures does not appear to vary significantly depending on whether the abortion is performed by a doctor or a mid-level practitioner.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Complications after second trimester abortion are similar to those after first trimester abortion, and depend somewhat on the method chosen.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The risk of death from abortion approaches roughly half the risk of death from childbirth the farther along a woman is in pregnancy; from one in a million before 9 weeks gestation to nearly one in ten thousand at 21 weeks or more (as measured from the last menstrual period).
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] It appears that having had a prior surgical uterine evacuation (whether because of induced abortion or treatment of miscarriage) correlates with a small increase in the risk of preterm birth in future pregnancies.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The studies supporting this did not control for factors not related to abortion or miscarriage, and hence the causes of this correlation have not been determined, although multiple possibilities have been suggested.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Current evidence finds no relationship between most induced abortions and mental health problems other than those expected for any unwanted pregnancy.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Some older reviews concluded that abortion was associated with an increased risk of psychological problems; however, later reviews of the medical literature found that previous reviews did not use an appropriate control group.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] When a control group is utilized, receiving abortion is not associated with adverse psychological outcomes.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] However, women seeking abortion who are denied access to abortion have an increase in anxiety after the denial.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Although some studies show negative mental-health outcomes in women who choose abortions after the first trimester because of fetal abnormalities, more rigorous research would be needed to show this conclusively.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Some proposed negative psychological effects of abortion have been referred to by anti-abortion advocates as a separate condition called "post-abortion syndrome", but this is not recognized by medical or psychological professionals in the United States.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] A 2020 long term-study among US women found that about 99% of women felt that they made the right decision five years after they had an abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Relief was the primary emotion with few women feeling sadness or guilt.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Social stigma was a main factor predicting negative emotions and regret years later.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Some purported risks of abortion are promoted primarily by anti-abortion groups, but lack scientific support.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] For example, the question of a link between induced abortion and breast cancer has been investigated extensively.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Major medical and scientific bodies (including the WHO, National Cancer Institute, American Cancer Society, Royal College of OBGYN and American Congress of OBGYN) have concluded that abortion does not cause breast cancer.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In the past even illegality has not automatically meant that the abortions were unsafe.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] A 1940s American physician spoke of his pride in having performed 13,844 illegal abortions without any fatalities.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In 1870s New York City, the abortionist/midwife Madame Restell (Anna Trow Lohman) is said to have lost very few women among her more than 100,000 patients—a lower mortality rate than the childbirth mortality rate at the time.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In 1936, obstetrics and gynecology professor Frederick J.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Women seeking an abortion may use unsafe methods, especially when abortion is legally restricted.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] They may attempt self-induced abortion or seek the help of a person without proper medical training or facilities.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] This can lead to severe complications, such as incomplete abortion, sepsis, hemorrhage, and damage to internal organs.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are a major cause of injury and death among women worldwide.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Although data are imprecise, it is estimated that approximately 20 million unsafe abortions are performed annually, with 97% taking place in developing countries.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are believed to result in millions of injuries.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Estimates of deaths vary according to methodology, and have ranged from 37,000 to 70,000 in the past decade; deaths from unsafe abortion account for around 13% of all maternal deaths.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization believes that mortality has fallen since the 1990s.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] To reduce the number of unsafe abortions, public health organizations have generally advocated emphasizing the legalization of abortion, training of medical personnel, and ensuring access to reproductive-health services.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] A major factor in whether abortions are performed safely or not is the legal standing of abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Countries with restrictive abortion laws have higher rates of unsafe abortion and similar overall abortion rates compared to countries where abortion is legal and available.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] For example, the 1996 legalization of abortion in South Africa led to an immediate reduction in abortion-related complications, with abortion-related deaths dropping by more than 90%.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Similar reductions in maternal mortality have been observed after other countries have liberalized their abortion laws, such as Romania and Nepal.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] A 2011 study concluded that in the United States, some state-level anti-abortion laws are correlated with lower rates of abortion in that state.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The analysis, however, did not take into account travel to other states without such laws to obtain an abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In addition, a lack of access to effective contraception contributes to unsafe abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] It has been estimated that the incidence of unsafe abortion could be reduced by up to 75% (from 20 million to 5 million annually) if modern family planning and maternal health services were readily available globally.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Rates of such abortions may be difficult to measure because they can be reported variously as miscarriage, "induced miscarriage", "menstrual regulation", "mini-abortion", and "regulation of a delayed/suspended menstruation".
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Forty percent of the world's women are able to access therapeutic and elective abortions within gestational limits, while an additional 35 percent have access to legal abortion if they meet certain physical, mental, or socioeconomic criteria.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] While maternal mortality seldom results from safe abortions, unsafe abortions result in 70,000 deaths and 5 million disabilities per year.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Complications of unsafe abortion account for approximately an eighth of maternal mortalities worldwide, though this varies by region.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Secondary infertility caused by an unsafe abortion affects an estimated 24 million women.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The rate of unsafe abortions has increased from 44% to 49% between 1995 and 2008.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Health education, access to family planning, and improvements in health care during and after abortion have been proposed to address consequences of unsafe abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In many places, where abortion is illegal or carries a heavy social stigma, medical reporting of abortion is not reliable.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] For this reason, estimates of the incidence of abortion must be made without determining certainty related to standard error.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The number of abortions performed worldwide was characterized as stable in the early 2000s, with 41.6 million having been performed in 2003 and 43.8 million having been performed in 2008.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The abortion rate worldwide was 28 per 1000 women per year, though it was 24 per 1000 women per year for developed countries and 29 per 1000 women per year for developing countries.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The same 2012 study indicated that in 2008, the estimated abortion percentage of known pregnancies was at 21% worldwide, with 26% in developed countries and 20% in developing countries.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] On average, the incidence of abortion is similar in countries with restrictive abortion laws and those with more liberal access to abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Restrictive abortion laws are associated with increases in the percentage of abortions performed unsafely.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The rate of legal, induced abortion varies extensively worldwide.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] According to the report of employees of Guttmacher Institute it ranged from 7 per 1000 women per year (Germany and Switzerland) to 30 per 1000 women per year (Estonia) in countries with complete statistics in 2008.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The proportion of pregnancies that ended in induced abortion ranged from about 10% (Israel, the Netherlands and Switzerland) to 30% (Estonia) in the same group, though it might be as high as 36% in Hungary and Romania, whose statistics were deemed incomplete.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] An American study in 2002 concluded that about half of women having abortions were using a form of contraception at the time of becoming pregnant.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Inconsistent use was reported by half of those using condoms and three-quarters of those using the birth control pill; 42% of those using condoms reported failure through slipping or breakage.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Of the other half of women, who were not using contraception at the time of becoming pregnant, the vast majority had used contraception at some point in the past, indicating some level of dissatisfaction with the contraceptive options available to them.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Indeed, 32% of these contraceptive nonusers cited concerns about contraceptive methods as their reason for nonuse, and a more recent study found similar results.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Taken together, these statistics suggest that new contraceptive methods, such as non-hormonal contraceptives or male contraceptives, could reduce unintended pregnancy and abortion rates.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute has found that "most abortions in the United States are obtained by minority women" because minority women "have much higher rates of unintended pregnancy".
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] in England and Wales during 2019 (left).
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Abortion in the United States by gestational age, 2016 (right).
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Abortion rates vary depending on the stage of pregnancy and the method practiced.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] 91% of these were classified as having been done by "curettage" (suction-aspiration, dilation and curettage, dilation and evacuation), 8% by "medical" means (mifepristone), >1% by "intrauterine instillation" (saline or prostaglandin), and 1% by "other" (including hysterotomy and hysterectomy).
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] According to the CDC, due to data collection difficulties the data must be viewed as tentative and some fetal deaths reported beyond 20 weeks may be natural deaths erroneously classified as abortions if the removal of the dead fetus is accomplished by the same procedure as an induced abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute estimated there were 2,200 intact dilation and extraction procedures in the US during 2000; this accounts for <0.2% of the total number of abortions performed that year.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Similarly, in England and Wales in 2006, 89% of terminations occurred at or under 12 weeks, 9% between 13 and 19 weeks, and 2% at or over 20 weeks.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] 64% of those reported were by vacuum aspiration, 6% by D&E, and 30% were medical.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] There are more second trimester abortions in developing countries such as China, India and Vietnam than in developed countries.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] There are both medical and non-medical reasons to have an abortion later in pregnancy (after 20 weeks).
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] A study was conducted from 2008 to 2010 at the University of California San Francisco where more than 440 women were asked about why they experienced delays in obtaining abortion care, if there were any.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] This study found that almost half of individuals who obtained an abortion after 20 weeks did not suspect that they were pregnant until later in their pregnancy.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Other barriers to abortion care found in the study included lack of information about where to access an abortion, difficulties with transportation, lack of insurance coverage, and inability to pay for the abortion procedure.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Medical reasons for seeking an abortion later in pregnancy include fetal anomalies and health risk to the pregnant person.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] There are prenatal tests that can diagnose Down Syndrome or cystic fibrosis as early as 10 weeks into gestation, but structural fetal anomalies are often detected much later in pregnancy.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] A proportion of structural fetal anomalies are lethal, which means that the fetus will almost certainly die before or shortly after birth.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Life-threatening conditions may also develop later in pregnancy, such as early severe preeclampsia, newly diagnosed cancer in need of urgent treatment, and intrauterine infection (chorioamnionitis), which often occurs along with premature rupture of the amniotic sac (PPROM).
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] If serious medical conditions such as these arise before the fetus is viable, the person carrying the pregnancy may pursue an abortion to preserve their own health.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The reasons why women have abortions are diverse and vary across the world.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Some of the reasons may include an inability to afford a child, domestic violence, lack of support, feeling they are too young, and the wish to complete education or advance a career.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Additional reasons include not being able or willing to raise a child conceived as a result of rape or incest.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Some abortions are undergone as the result of societal pressures.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] These factors can sometimes result in compulsory abortion or sex-selective abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In cultures where there is a preference for male children, some women have sex selective abortions, which have partially replaced the earlier practice of female infanticide.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Some abortions are performed due to concerns over maternal health.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In 1990s, women cited maternal health as their main motivating factor in about a third of abortions in three of 27 countries analyzed.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In seven additional countries, about 7% of abortions were maternal health related.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In the U.S., the Supreme Court decisions in *Roe v.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Bolton*: "ruled that the state's interest in the life of the fetus became compelling only at the point of viability, defined as the point at which the fetus can survive independently of its mother.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Even after the point of viability, the state cannot favor the life of the fetus over the life or health of the pregnant woman.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Under the right of privacy, physicians must be free to use their "medical judgment for the preservation of the life or health of the mother".
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] On the same day that the Court decided Roe, it also decided Doe v.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Bolton, in which the Court defined health very broadly: "The medical judgment may be exercised in the light of all factors—physical, emotional, psychological, familial, and the woman's age—relevant to the well-being of the patient.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The rate of cancer during pregnancy is 0.02–1%, and in many cases, cancer of the mother leads to consideration of abortion to protect the life of the mother, or in response to the potential damage that may occur to the fetus during treatment.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] This is particularly true for cervical cancer, the most common type of which occurs in 1 of every 2,000–13,000 pregnancies, for which initiation of treatment "cannot co-exist with preservation of fetal life (unless neoadjuvant chemotherapy is chosen)".
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Very early stage cervical cancers (I and IIa) may be treated by radical hysterectomy and pelvic lymph node dissection, radiation therapy, or both, while later stages are treated by radiotherapy.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Chemotherapy may be used simultaneously.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Treatment of breast cancer during pregnancy also involves fetal considerations, because lumpectomy is discouraged in favor of modified radical mastectomy unless late-term pregnancy allows follow-up radiation therapy to be administered after the birth.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Exposure to a single chemotherapy drug is estimated to cause a 7.5–17% risk of teratogenic effects on the fetus, with higher risks for multiple drug treatments.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Treatment with more than 40 Gy of radiation usually causes spontaneous abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Exposure to much lower doses during the first trimester, especially 8 to 15 weeks of development, can cause intellectual disability or microcephaly, and exposure at this or subsequent stages can cause reduced intrauterine growth and birth weight.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Exposures above 0.005–0.025 Gy cause a dose-dependent reduction in IQ.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] It is possible to greatly reduce exposure to radiation with abdominal shielding, depending on how far the area to be irradiated is from the fetus.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The process of birth itself may also put the mother at risk.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Congenital disorders, revealed by prenatal screening, motivate some women to seek abortions.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Health outcomes of preterm births include a significant probability of long-term neurodevelopmental impairment before gestational age of 29 weeks, with a higher probability with decreasing gestational age.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In the United States, public opinion shifted after television personality Sherri Finkbine's was exposed to thalidomide, a teratogen, in her fifth month of pregnancy.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Unable to obtain a legal abortion in the United States, Finkbine traveled to Sweden.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] From 1962 to 1965, an outbreak of German measles left 15,000 babies with severe birth defects.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In 1967, the American Medical Association publicly supported liberalization of abortion laws.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] A National Opinion Research Center poll in 1965 showed 73% supported abortion when the mother's life was at risk, 57% when birth defects were present and 59% for pregnancies resulting from rape or incest.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Since ancient times, abortions have been done using a number of methods, including herbal medicines acting as abortifacients, sharp tools through the use of force, or through other traditional medicine methods.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Induced abortion has a long history and can be traced back to civilizations as varied as ancient China (abortifacient knowledge is often attributed to the mythological ruler Shennong), ancient India since its Vedic age, ancient Egypt with its Ebers Papyrus (c.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] 1550 BCE), and the Roman Empire in the time of Juvenal (c.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] One of the earliest known artistic representations of abortion is in a bas relief at Angkor Wat (c.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Found in a series of friezes that represent judgment after death in Hindu and Buddhist culture, it depicts the technique of abdominal abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In *Politics* (350 BCE), Aristotle condemned infanticide as a means of population control.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] He preferred abortion in such cases, with the restriction that it "must be practised on it before it has developed sensation and life; for the line between lawful and unlawful abortion will be marked by the fact of having sensation and being alive".
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Abortion has been a fairly common practice, and was not always illegal or controversial until the 19th century.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In Europe and North America, abortion techniques advanced starting in the 17th century; the conservatism of most in the medical profession with regards to sexual matters prevented the wide expansion of abortion techniques.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Other medical practitioners in addition to some physicians advertised their services, and they were not widely regulated until the 19th century when the practice, sometimes called *restellism*, was banned in both the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Some 19th-century physicians, argued for anti-abortion laws on racist and misogynist as well as moral grounds.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Church groups were also highly influential in anti-abortion movements, and religious groups more so since the 20th century.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Some of the early anti-abortion laws punished only the doctor or abortionist, and while women could be criminally tried for a self-induced abortion, they were rarely prosecuted in general.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Some maintain that in the 19th century early abortions under the hygienic conditions in which midwives usually worked were relatively safe.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Several scholars argue that, despite improved medical procedures, the period from the 1930s until the 1970s saw more zealous enforcement of anti-abortion laws, alongside an increasing control of abortion providers by organized crime.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In 1920, Soviet Russia became the first country to legalize abortion after Lenin insisted that no woman be forced to give birth.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Abortion was then legalized in some form in Iceland (1935), Sweden (1938), Nazi Germany (1935) and Japan (1948) Beginning in the second half of the 20th century, abortion was legalized in a greater number of countries.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In the Catholic Church, opinion was divided on how serious abortion was in comparison with such acts as contraception and oral or anal sex.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The Catholic Church did not begin vigorously opposing abortion until the 19th century.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] As early as ~100 CE, the *Didache* taught that abortion was sinful.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Several historians argue that prior to the 19th century most Catholic authors did not regard termination of pregnancy before quickening or ensoulment as an abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] 1585–1590) was the first Pope to institute a Church policy labeling all abortion as homicide and condemning abortion regardless of the stage of pregnancy.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Sixtus V's pronouncement was reversed in 1591 by Pope Gregory XIV.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In the recodification of 1917 Code of Canon Law, *Apostolicae Sedis* was strengthened, in part to remove a possible reading that excluded excommunication of the mother.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Statements made in the *Catechism of the Catholic Church*, the codified summary of the Church's teachings, considers abortion from the moment of conception as homicide and called for the end of legal abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Denominations that support abortion rights with some limits include the United Methodist Church, Episcopal Church, Evangelical Lutheran Church in America and Presbyterian Church USA.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] A 2014 Guttmacher survey of abortion patients in the United States found that many reported a religious affiliation: 24% were Catholic while 30% were Protestant.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] A 1995 survey reported that Catholic women are as likely as the general population to terminate a pregnancy, Protestants are less likely to do so, and evangelical Christians are the least likely to do so.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] A 2019 Pew Research Center study found that most Christian denominations were against overturning *Roe v.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Wade,* which in the United States legalized abortion, at around 70%, except White Evangelicals at 35%.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In Judaism, the fetus is not considered to have a human soul until it is safely outside of the woman, is viable, and has taken its first breath.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] The fetus is considered valuable property of the woman and not a human life while in the womb (Exodus 21:22-23).
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] While Judaism encourages people to be fruitful and multiply by having children, abortion is allowed and is deemed necessary when a pregnant woman's life is in danger.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Several religions, including Judaism, which disagree that human life begins at conception, support the legality of abortion on religious freedom grounds.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] In Islam, abortion is traditionally permitted until a point in time when Muslims believe the soul enters the fetus, considered by various theologians to be at conception, 40 days after conception, 120 days after conception, or at quickening.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Abortion is largely heavily restricted or forbidden in areas of high Islamic faith such as the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Hindu views on abortion are diverse and lack a single authoritative position, shaped by principles like ahimsa (non-violence), karma, and reincarnation, which typically regard it as morally wrong for interrupting the soul's cycle.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Scriptures often equate abortion to grave sins, with the fetus considered ensouled from conception or early gestation.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] However, it may be ethically permissible to save the mother's life or in cases of severe fetal abnormalities, prioritizing lesser harm.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p01] Modern opinions differ regionally: In India, a majority view abortion as generally illegal, while in the US, most Hindus support legal access in all or most cases.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Induced abortion has long been the source of considerable debate.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Ethical, moral, philosophical, biological, religious and legal issues surrounding abortion are related to value systems.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Opinions of abortion may be about fetal rights, governmental authority, and women's rights.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] In both public and private debate, arguments presented in favor of or against abortion access focus on either the moral permissibility of an induced abortion, or the justification of laws permitting or restricting abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] The World Medical Association Declaration on Therapeutic Abortion notes, "circumstances bringing the interests of a mother into conflict with the interests of her unborn child create a dilemma and raise the question as to whether or not the pregnancy should be deliberately terminated".
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Abortion debates, especially pertaining to abortion laws, are often spearheaded by groups advocating one of these two positions.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Groups who favor greater legal restrictions on abortion, including complete prohibition, most often describe themselves as "pro-life" while groups who are against such legal restrictions describe themselves as "pro-choice".
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] The median voters stance on abortion varies by jurisdiction and can result in swing votes.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Current laws pertaining to abortion are diverse.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Religious, moral, and cultural factors continue to influence abortion laws throughout the world.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] The right to life, the right to liberty, the right to security of person, and the right to reproductive health are major issues of human rights that sometimes constitute the basis for the existence or absence of abortion laws.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] In jurisdictions where abortion is legal, certain requirements must often be met before a woman may obtain a legal abortion (an abortion performed without the woman's consent is considered feticide and is generally illegal).
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] These requirements usually depend on the age of the fetus, often using a trimester-based system to regulate the window of legality, or as in the U.S., on a doctor's evaluation of the fetus' viability.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Some jurisdictions require a waiting period before the procedure, prescribe the distribution of information on fetal development, or require that parents be contacted if their minor daughter requests an abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Many restrictions are waived in emergency situations.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] China, which has ended their one-child policy, and now has a three-child policy, has at times incorporated mandatory abortions as part of their population control strategy.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Other jurisdictions ban abortion almost entirely.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Many, but not all, of these allow legal abortions in a variety of circumstances.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] These circumstances vary based on jurisdiction, but may include whether the pregnancy is a result of rape or incest, the fetus' development is impaired, the woman's physical or mental well-being is endangered, or socioeconomic considerations make childbirth a hardship.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] In countries where abortion is banned entirely, such as Nicaragua, medical authorities have recorded rises in maternal death directly and indirectly due to pregnancy as well as deaths due to doctors' fears of prosecution if they treat other gynecological emergencies.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Some countries, such as Bangladesh, that nominally ban abortion, may also support clinics that perform abortions under the guise of menstrual hygiene.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] This is also a terminology in traditional medicine.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] In places where abortion is illegal or carries heavy social stigma, pregnant women may engage in medical tourism and travel to countries where they can terminate their pregnancies.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Women on Waves has provided medication abortion and education on a ship in international waters off the coast of countries with restrictive abortion laws.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Women without the means to travel can resort to providers of illegal abortions or attempt to perform an abortion by themselves.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Sonography and amniocentesis allow parents to determine sex before childbirth.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] The development of this technology has led to sex-selective abortion, or the termination of a fetus based on its sex.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] The selective termination of a female fetus is most common.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Sex-selective abortion is partially responsible for the noticeable disparities between the birth rates of male and female children in some countries.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] The preference for male children is reported in many areas of Asia, and abortion used to limit female births has been reported in Taiwan, South Korea, India, and China.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] This deviation from the standard birth rates of males and females occurs despite the fact that the country in question may have officially banned sex-selective abortion or even sex-screening.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Many countries have taken legislative steps to reduce the incidence of sex-selective abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] At the International Conference on Population and Development in 1994 over 180 states agreed to eliminate "all forms of discrimination against the girl child and the root causes of son preference", conditions also condemned by a PACE resolution in 2011.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] On the other hand, measures to reduce gender inequality can reduce the prevalence of such abortions without attendant negative consequences.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Abortion providers and facilities have been subjected to violence, including murder, assault, arson, and bombing.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Some scholars consider anti-abortion violence to be within the definition of terrorism, a view shared by some governments.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] In the U.S. and Canada, over 8,000 incidents of violence, trespassing, and death threats have been recorded by providers since 1977, including over 200 bombings/arsons and hundreds of assaults.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Abortion clinics have also been targeted by acid attacks, invasions, and vandalism The majority of abortion opponents have not been involved in violent acts.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Physicians and other abortion clinic staff have been murdered by abortion opponents.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] In the United States, at least four physicians have been murdered in connection with their work at abortion clinics, including David Gunn (1993), John Britton (1994), Barnett Slepian (1998), and George Tiller (2009).
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] In Canada, gynecologist Garson Romalis survived murder attempts in both 1994 and 2000.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Besides physicians, killings have targeted other clinic staff, such as John Salvi's 1994 murder of two receptionists in Massachusetts clinic and Peter Knight's 2001 murder of a security guard in a Melbourne clinic.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Notable perpetrators of anti-abortion violence include Eric Rudolph, Scott Roeder, Shelley Shannon, and Paul Hill, the first person to be executed in the United States for murdering an abortion provider.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Some countries have laws to protecting access to abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Such laws prevent abortion opponents from interfering with access to legal abortion services.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] For example, the American Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act bars the use of threats or violence to interfere with abortion access.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Abortion access laws may also establish safe access zones around abortion clinics, with limits on protests and enhanced penalties for anti-abortion violence.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Psychological pressure may also be used to limit abortion access.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Some protestors record women entering clinics on camera.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Spontaneous abortion occurs in various animals.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] For example, in sheep it may be caused by stress or physical exertion, such as crowding through doors or being chased by dogs.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] In cows, abortion may be caused by contagious disease, such as brucellosis or *Campylobacter*, but can often be controlled by vaccination.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Eating pine needles can also induce abortions in cows.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Several plants, including broomweed, skunk cabbage, poison hemlock, and tree tobacco, are known to cause fetal deformities and abortion in cattle, and in sheep and goats.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] In horses, a fetus may be aborted or resorbed if it has lethal white syndrome.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Foal embryos that are homozygous for the dominant white gene (WW) are theorized to also be aborted or resorbed before birth.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] In many species of sharks and rays, stress-induced abortions occur frequently upon capture.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Viral infection can cause abortion in dogs.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Cats can experience spontaneous abortion for many reasons, including hormonal imbalance.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] A combined abortion and spaying are performed on pregnant cats, especially in trap–neuter–return programs, to prevent unwanted kittens from being born.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Female rodents may terminate a pregnancy when exposed to the smell of a male not responsible for the pregnancy, known as the Bruce effect.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Abortion may also be induced in animals, in the context of animal husbandry.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] For example, abortion may be induced in mares that have been mated improperly, or that have been purchased by owners who did not realize the mares were pregnant, or that are pregnant with twin foals.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Feticide can occur in horses and zebras due to male harassment of pregnant mares or forced copulation, although the frequency in the wild has been questioned.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-p02] Male gray langur monkeys may attack females following male takeover, causing miscarriage.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The issue of induced abortion remains divisive in public life, with recurring arguments to liberalize or restrict access to legal abortion services.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Some abortion-rights supporters are divided as to the types of abortion services that should be available under different circumstances, including periods in the pregnancy such as late term abortions, in which access may or may not be restricted.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Many of the terms used in the debate are political framing terms used to validate one's stance while invalidating the opposition.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] For example, the labels pro-choice and pro-life imply endorsement of widely held values such as liberty and freedom, while suggesting that the opposition must be "anti-choice" or "anti-life".
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] These views do not always align along a strict binary.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] In one poll conducted by the Public Religion Research Institute, the ambiguity of the terms led 70% of Americans to identify as 'pro-choice,' while nearly two-thirds simultaneously identified as "pro-life".
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] It was found that, in polling, respondents would label themselves differently when given specific details about the circumstances around an abortion including factors such as rape, incest, viability of the fetus, and survivability of the mother.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The Associated Press favors the terms "abortion rights" and "anti-abortion" instead.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Abortion practices date back to 1550 BCE, based on the findings of practices recorded on documents.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Abortion has been an active practice since Egyptian medicine.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Centuries later, abortion was a topic taken up by feminism.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Mohr, there was an earlier acceptance of abortion, and opposition to abortion, including anti-abortion laws, only came into being in the 19th century.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] It was not always a crime and was generally not illegal until quickening, which occurred between the fourth and sixth months of pregnancy.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] In the 19th century, the medical profession was generally opposed to abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Mohr argues that the opposition arose due to competition between men with medical degrees and women without one, such as Madame Drunette.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The practice of abortion was one of the first medical specialities, and was practiced by unlicensed people; well-off people had abortions and paid well.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The press played a key role in rallying support for anti-abortion laws.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The ideas of the legalization of abortion in the late 19th century were often opposed by feminists, seeing it as a means of relieving men of responsibility.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] In *The Revolution*, which was an official published newspaper of women's rights that went out weekly, operated by Elizabeth Cady Stanton and Susan B.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Anthony, an anonymous contributor signing "A" wrote in 1869 about the subject, arguing that instead of merely attempting to pass a law against abortion, the root cause must also be addressed.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] *The Revolution* newspaper highly impacted the women's rights movement, and for the first time, it seemed like women's voices were being heard through the proclamations of these unacknowledged subjects regarding women and their everyday rights and safety as citizens.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The writer wrote that simply passing an anti-abortion law would "be only mowing off the top of the noxious weed, while the root remains. ...
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] No matter what the motive, love of ease, or a desire to save from suffering the unborn innocent, the woman is awfully guilty who commits the deed.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Between 1900 and 1965, there were not any anti-abortion movements or rallies because states had already passed a law banning abortions at all levels, including prescriptions and procedures.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The only exception for a woman to get an abortion without fear of legal retribution was if a licensed physician determined the abortion would protect the mother's life.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Physicians who provide abortions and women who have abortions were constantly harassed by courts and prosecutors.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] In the 1960s, some states began to request changes with the abortion law.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] In 1959, a group of experts set up a model enactment that supported the advancement of the abortion laws.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] These experts suggested that the abortion laws should provide exemptions for women that were sexually assaulted or for a baby that may not have a good quality of life.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The abortion-rights movement became a controversial topic in the United States regarding abortion and reproduction.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The movement towards the liberalization of abortion law emerged in the 1920s and 1930s in the context of the victories that had been recently won in the area of birth control.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Campaigners including Marie Stopes in England and Margaret Sanger in the US had succeeded in bringing the issue into the open, and birth control clinics were established that offered family planning advice and contraceptive methods to women in need.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Birth control is a method of pregnancy prevention through controlled contraception.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] In 1929, the Infant Life Preservation Act was passed in the United Kingdom, which amended the law (Offences against the Person Act 1861) so that an abortion carried out in good faith, for the sole purpose of preserving the life of the mother, would not be an offense.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Many citizens had mixed opinions on this, but ultimately started protesting this as child destruction.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Child destruction was known as taking the life of a viable unborn child during a pregnancy or at birth, before it is independent of its mother.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] If there is an intent of death and no good faith is carried out in the process in order to protect the mother's livelihood, the offense carries a maximum punishment of life imprisonment.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The Infant Life Preservation Act defines the difference between murder and abortion-the causing of a miscarriage.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Stella Browne was a leading birth control campaigner, who increasingly began to venture into the more contentious issue of abortion in the 1930s.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Browne's beliefs were heavily influenced by the work of Havelock Ellis, Edward Carpenter and other sexologists.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] She came to strongly believe that working women should have the choice to become pregnant and to terminate their pregnancy while they worked in the horrible circumstances surrounding a pregnant woman who was still required to do hard labor during her pregnancy.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] In this case she argued that doctors should give free information about birth control to women that wanted to know about it.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] This would give women agency over their own circumstances and allow them to decide whether they wanted to be mothers or not.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] These talks urged women to take matters of their sexuality and their health into their own hands.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] She became increasingly interested in her view of the woman's right to terminate their pregnancies, and in 1929, she brought forward her lecture "The Right to Abortion" in front of the World Sexual Reform Congress in London.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] In 1931, Browne began to develop her argument for women's right to decide to have an abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] She again began touring, giving lectures on abortion and the negative consequences that followed if women were unable to terminate pregnancies of their own choosing such as: suicide, injury, permanent invalidism, madness and blood-poisoning.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] On February 17, 1936, Janet Chance, Alice Jenkins and Joan Malleson established the Abortion Law Reform Association as the first advocacy organization for abortion liberalization.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The association promoted access to abortion in the United Kingdom and campaigned for the elimination of legal obstacles.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] In its first year ALRA recruited 35 members, and by 1939 had almost 400 members.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The ALRA was very active between 1936 and 1939 sending speakers around the country to talk about Labour and Equal Citizenship and attempted, though most often unsuccessfully, to have letters and articles published in newspapers.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] They became the most popular when a member of the ALRA's Medico-Legal Committee received the case of a fourteen-year-old girl who had been raped, and received a termination of this pregnancy from Dr.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Joan Malleson, a progenitor of the ALRA.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] In 1938, Joan Malleson precipitated one of the most influential cases in British abortion law when she referred a pregnant fourteen-year old rape survivor to gynaecologist Aleck Bourne.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] He performed an abortion, then illegal, and was put on trial on charges of procuring abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Bourne was eventually acquitted in *R v.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Bourne*as his actions were "...an example of disinterested conduct in consonance with the highest traditions of the profession".
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] This court case set a precedent that doctors could not be prosecuted for performing an abortion in cases where pregnancy would probably cause "mental and physical wreck".
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The Abortion Law Reform Association continued its campaigning after the Second World War, and this, combined with broad social changes brought the issue of abortion back into the political arena in the 1960s.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] In America an abortion reform movement emerged in the 1960s.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] In 1964, Gerri Santoro of Connecticut died trying to obtain an illegal abortion and her photo became the symbol of the abortion rights movement.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Some women's rights activist groups developed their own skills to provide abortions to women who could not obtain them elsewhere.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] As an example, in Chicago, a group known as "Jane" operated a floating abortion clinic throughout much of the 1960s.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Women seeking the procedure would call a designated number and be given instructions on how to find "Jane".
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] In the late 1960s, a number of organizations were formed to mobilize opinion both against and for the legalization of abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The forerunner of the NARAL Pro-Choice America was formed in 1969 to oppose restrictions on abortion and expand access to abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] In late 1973, NARAL became the National Abortion Rights Action League.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The landmark judicial ruling of the Supreme Court in *Roe v.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Wade* ruled that a Texas statute forbidding abortion except when necessary to save the life of the mother was unconstitutional.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] This was back in 1970, where Jane Roe, (which was actually a fictional name used in the court documents in order to protect the plaintiff's identity), had filed a lawsuit against Henry Wade.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] He was the district attorney of Dallas County in Texas, where Jane Roe resided.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] She was challenging a Texas law making abortion illegal except by a doctor's orders to save a woman's life.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The Court arrived at its decision by concluding that the issue of abortion and abortion rights falls under the right to privacy.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The Court held that a right to privacy existed and included the right to have an abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The court found that a mother had a right to abortion until viability, a point to be determined by the abortion doctor.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] After viability a woman can obtain an abortion for health reasons, which the Court defined broadly to include psychological well-being in the decision *Doe v.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] From the 1970s, and the spread of second-wave feminism, abortion and reproductive rights became unifying issues among various women's rights groups in Canada, the United States, the Netherlands, Britain, Norway, France, Germany, and Italy.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] In 2015, in the wake of the House of Representatives' vote to defund Planned Parenthood, Lindy West, Amelia Bonow and Kimberly Morrison launched ShoutYourAbortion to "remind supporters and critics alike abortion is a legal right to anyone who wants or needs it".
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] In 2019, the You Know Me movement started as a response to the successful 2019 passage of fetal heartbeat bills in five states in the United States, most notably the passing of anti-abortion laws in Georgia (House Bill 381), Ohio (House Bill 68) and Alabama (House Bill 314).
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] This movement was started off by actress Busy Philipps because she had previously had an abortion when she was a teen.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The actress and many others believe that it is important for women to speak up and shift the narrative, especially because abortion is such a taboo subject.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] In the mid-19th century, concerns around abortion only consisted of the danger of a woman being poisoned and risking her health, not because of religion, ethics, or diplomacy.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Ending a pregnancy before the fetus began movement, or "post-quickening" was only a wrongdoing, not a crime.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The laws that were against abortions post-quickening removals were put in place to protect the well-being of the women that were pregnant, not the fetal life.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] It was more common for women to die during early terminations due to the usage of pre-owned instruments as opposed to natural abortifacients.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Some women who engaged in quickening abortions were not prosecuted because there was no evidence and quickening was hard to prove.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Between 1900 and 1965, there were not any anti-abortion movements or rallies because states had already passed a law banning abortions at all levels included the prescription of drugs or undergoing procedures.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The only exception for a woman to proceed with an abortion without worrying about breaking any anti-abortion laws is if a licensed physician were to prove that the abortion was for the protection of the mother's life.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Abortion care providers and women who had obtained an abortion were pestered by courts and prosecutors.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] In the 1960s, some states began to request changes, around the abortion law, from their states.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] In 1959, a group of experts set up a model enactment that supported the advancement of the fetus removal laws that were put in place.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] These experts suggested that the abortion laws should exempt women that were sexually assaulted, whose babies well-being were to be questioned and whose babies that were to be born out of its true, natural or original state.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The Abortion Rights Movement became a cultural shift in The United States about the intentions of reproduction and abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Wade* verdict changed the abortion laws altogether, making abortion legal.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Many physicians and healthcare professionals jeopardized their medical licenses, risked being put in prison and fined by the state because they wanted to continue to provide abortions.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] There were more than 1,000 abortion laws passed and enacted between 2011 and 2019 that limited access to abortion procedures.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Some of these laws forbid a woman getting an abortion past a certain gestational age and was also based on race and specific pregnancy conditions.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Other laws were established that ban particular abortion methods.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Targeted regulation of abortion providers (TRAP) was put in place to target abortion clinics by demanding unnecessary requirements that made it hard for women to get an abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Opponents of abortion rights claim that these requirements are for the safety of the mother and child, but that has not been scientifically proven.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] TRAP has placed limitations on abortion facilities to make it more difficult for them to provide abortion services that will essentially force them to not provide abortion services at all.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] TRAP policies have been put in place by 26 states as of 2020.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] During the pandemic, numerous states prohibited non-essential medical procedures, including abortion services.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Policymakers in twelve states saw this as a chance to certify abortion as non-essential, therefore ending services.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Jackson Women's Health Organization overturned Roe v.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Wade, removing the federal constitutional right to abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] This left abortion laws and restrictions up to each individual state.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] South Africa allows abortion on demand under its Choice on Termination of Pregnancy Act.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Most African nations, however, have abortion bans except in cases where the woman's life or health is at risk.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] A number of abortion-rights international organizations have made altering abortion laws and expanding family planning services in sub-Saharan Africa and the developing world a top priority.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] But there are only five countries in Africa where abortion is legal and those countries are Cape Verde, South Africa, Tunisia, Mozambique and Saõ Tome & Principe.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] 8.2 million abortions were performed each year in Africa.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] This number increased drastically compared to the 4.6 million abortions that were performed during 1990–1994.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] But this increased number of abortions is due to the increase of women that are reproducing at a young age.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Approximately 93% of women within their reproductive age live in countries that have very restrictive abortion laws and abortion is only legal in 10 out of 54 African countries, leading to fewer women not being able to obtain a safe procedure.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The World Health Organization only recommends trained personnel when performing induced abortions but not many women in Africa have access to trained professionals who are able to provide them with the best service to decrease the number of complications due to abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Approximately 1.6 million women are treated for abortion-related complications and only one in four abortions in Africa are safe.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Africa has the highest number of deaths that are related to abortion and this is due to the most common complication of abortion that consist of excessive blood loss and an incomplete abortion that can lead to an infection.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] During 2010–2014, 36 million abortions were performed in Asia.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Majority of abortions occurred in Central and South Asia at a rate of 16 million in India and Asia and 13 million in China alone.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Although the abortions performed in Asia are not known, there is an estimated 4.6 million women who are treated because they have complications due to the performance of an unsafe abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The major complication of abortion is an incomplete abortion where a woman can experience an immoderate amount of blood loss and can develop an infection.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Less common complications of abortion include a woman going into septic shock, damaging the internal organs and causing the peritoneum to be inflamed, all due to the unclean and unsterilized instruments that are being used doing the procedure.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Untreated complications from abortions can leave women to experience negative health consequences for life that include infertility, chronic pain, inflammation of the reproductive organs and pelvic inflammatory disease.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Unsafe abortions go deeper than just a woman's health but they lead to reduced productivity for women increased costs to an already struggling family.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Although it is not completely known, a drug known as misoprostol is used to perform abortions in Asian countries and evidence shows that the sales of this drug has increased in Asia over the course of years.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] On record, out of all the pregnancies in Asia, 27 percent of them end in abortions.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] This is the reason for the Asia Safe Abortion Partnership (ASAP).
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] This program was formed to increase the accessibility to safe and legal abortions and health care that is needed after any abortion service.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] 50 countries occupy Asia and out of those 50, 17 countries do not have a restriction on abortions excluding, gestational limits and permission from a spouse or parent.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] ASAP satisfies the demand for safe and accessible abortions through educational and advocacy.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] By grouping with other countries to promote advocacy networks, ASAP has created a worldwide and generational feminist power that advocates for women's abortion rights, autonomy and dignity.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Anti-abortion groups have tried their best to discriminate the reproductive autonomy of women but ASAP has members spread across 20 countries that promote the women's movement for abortion rights, laws, and access.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Even though abortion is legal in Asia, that does not mean that women always have access or adequate health care during these times.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] For example, abortions in India have been legal since 1951 but women who are particularly poor or marginalized make up 50% of unsafe abortions.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Women in the Philippines are more than likely to undergo an unsafe and unsanitary abortion causing around 1,000 death annually due to abortion complications.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The Philippines along with Iraq and Laos are the countries that has not made abortion legal, excluding legal exceptions, therefore they have not made it available to where women can have admissions to legal abortions that are safe for them and their bodies.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Countries such as Afghanistan, Thailand, China and Lebanon, have all been impacted by the determined long-term feminist motion by ASAP for women's abortion rights.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] This work ranges from workshops, journalists, advocates to menstrual management, violence against women, and issues surrounded unplanned pregnancies.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] "Youth champions" were created by ASAP to share the knowledge that they have learned to their peers about sexual activity, abortions, women's rights and reproductions, reproductive health, and the abortion rights movement in general.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Chapter XXIX of the Penal Code of Japan makes abortion illegal in Japan.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Other people, including the mother herself, trying to abort the fetus can be punished by the law.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] People trying to practice abortion without the consent of the woman can also be punished, including the doctors.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Abortion has been illegal in South Korea since 1953 but on April 11, 2019, South Korea's Constitutional Court ruled the abortion ban unconstitutional and called for the law to be amended.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The Constitutional Court has taken into consideration abortion-rights cases by women because they find the abortion ban as unconstitutional.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] To help support the legalization of abortion in South Korea, thousands of advocates compiled a petition for the Blue House to consider lifting the ban.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Due to the abortion ban, this has led to many dangerous self-induced abortions and other illegal practices of abortion that needs more attention.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] This is why there are advocates challenging the law to put into perspective the negative factors this abortion ban brings.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] By making abortion illegal in South Korea, this also creates an issue when it comes to women's rights and their own rights to their bodies.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] As a result, many women's advocate groups were created and acted together to protest against the abortion ban law.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Global Day of Action is a form of protest that advocates to make a change and bring more awareness to global warming.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] During this protest, a group of feminist Korean advocates called, "The Joint Action for Reproductive Justice" connected with one another to promote concerns that requires more attention and needs a quick change such as making abortion legal.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] By combining different advocate groups that serves different purposes and their own goals they want to achieve into one event, it helps promote all the different aspects of reality that needs to change.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] In 1920, under the leadership of Vladimir Lenin, Russia became the first country in the world to legally permit abortion, no matter the circumstances.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] But in the 20th century, the laws surrounding abortion were repeatedly modified between the years of 1936 and 1955.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] According to data from the United Nations in 2010, Russia had the highest rates of abortion per woman of reproduction.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Results from the abortion rates of China and Russia were compared and out of a population of 1.3 billion people, China only reported 13 million abortions, a huge difference when contrasted to the population in Russia of 143 million people with 1.2 million abortions.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Since abortion was illegal in the Russian Empire, it was not recognized in the Domostroi.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The Domostroi was a set of tasks that were to be followed that were structured around rules, instructions surrounded by religious, social and domestic issues that were centered within the Russian Society.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] These rules enforced respect and compliance to God and the church.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Different rulers had different views about abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] During Romanov's reign, abortion was illegal, frowned up, and if a woman were to go through with an abortion, her punishment was death.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] But after Romanov's reign ended, Peter the Great lifted the punishment of death for abortions but it was still considered a serious issue in 1917.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Before the punishment for abortions was death, according to the Russian Penal Code that dates back to 1462–1463, women were dispossessed of their basic human and civil rights and banned from the city or they were forced into hard labor.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] These harsh treatments and illegality surrounded around abortion still did not stop women from pursuing abortions.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] "Black Market" abortions were known as unauthorized and discreet procedures done by women who have experience in childbirth.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] These women were known as older women that were midwives and rural midwives, respectfully.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Although these women were not abortion care providers, they were the only accessible obstetric personnel that women could go to without facing the harsh punishment and consequences forced upon by the Russian Society.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Since adequate medical care was not provided for women looking to terminate their pregnancy, midwives and nurses from villages were trained to care for these women the best to their ability, but of course with illegal abortions there are always repercussions.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] During the Soviet period in Russia, abortions ranked as the highest rates world-wide.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] After the Soviet period ended inn the Russian union, abortion numbers decreased with further enforced sex education courses and use of contraceptive birth control.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Abortion was illegal in the Republic of Ireland except when the woman's life was threatened by a medical condition (including risk of suicide), since a 1983 referendum (aka 8th Amendment) amended the constitution.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Subsequent amendments in 1992 (after the X Case) – the thirteenth and fourteenth – guaranteed the right to travel abroad (for abortions) and to distribute and obtain information of "lawful services" available in other countries.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Two proposals to remove suicide risk as a ground for abortion were rejected by the people, in a referendum in 1992 and in 2002.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Thousands of women get around the ban by privately traveling to the other European countries (typically Britain and the Netherlands) to undergo termination, or by ordering abortion pills from Women on Web online and taking them in Ireland.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Sinn Féin, the Labour Party, Social Democrats, Green Party, Communist Party, Socialist Party and Irish Republican Socialist Party have made their official policies to support abortion rights.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Mainstream center-right parties such as Fianna Fáil and Fine Gael do not have official policies on abortion rights but allow their members to take a conscience vote in support of abortion in limited circumstances.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Aontú, founded in January 2019, is firmly anti-abortionist and seeks to "protect the right to life".
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] After the death of Savita Halappanavar in 2012, there has been a renewed campaign to repeal the eighth amendment and legalize abortion.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] As of January 2017, the Irish government has set up a citizens assembly to look at the issue.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Their proposals, broadly supported by a cross-party Oireachtas committee, include repeal of the 8th Amendment, unrestricted access to abortion for the first 12 weeks of pregnancy and no-term limits for special cases of fatal foetal abnormalities, rape and incest.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] A referendum on the repealing of the 8th Amendment was held on May 25, 2018.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Together for Yes, a cross-society group formed from the Coalition to Repeal the 8th Amendment, the National Women's Council of Ireland and the Abortion Rights Campaign, were the official campaign group for repeal in the referendum.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Activists utilized social media to bring the narrative of women's voices to the forefront of the campaign, making clear that the Eighth Amendment was dangerous for pregnant women to try and encourage voters to vote in favor of repeal.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The 67% majority in favor of repeal is a testament to these stories and the women who braved the public Twitter sphere to change the law around women's reproductive lives.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Despite being part of the United Kingdom, abortion remained illegal in Northern Ireland, except in cases when the woman is threatened by a medical condition, physical or mental, until 2019.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Women seeking abortions had to travel to England.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] In October 2019, abortion up to 12 weeks was legalized, to begin in April 2020, but remains near-unobtainable.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Poland initially held abortion to be legal in 1958 by the communist government, but was later banned after restoration of democracy in 1989.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Currently, abortion is illegal in all cases except for rape or when the fetus or mother is in fatal conditions.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The wide spread of Catholic Church in Poland within the country has made abortion socially 'unacceptable'.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The Pope has had major influence on the acceptance of abortion within Poland.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Several landmark court cases have had substantial influence on the current status of abortion, including *Tysiac v Poland*.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] In the United Kingdom, the Abortion Act 1967 legalized abortion on a wide number of grounds, except in Northern Ireland.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] 4. shows there is evidence of extreme fetal abnormality i.e. the child would be seriously physically or mentally handicapped after birth and during life.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] However, the criterion of risk to mental and physical health is applied broadly, and *de facto* makes abortion available on demand, though this still requires the consent of two National Health Service doctors.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Abortions in Great Britain are provided at no out-of-pocket cost to the patient by the NHS.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The Labour Party and the Liberal Democrats are predominantly pro-abortion-rights parties, though with significant minorities in each either holding more restrictive definitions of the right to choose, or subscribing to an anti-abortion analysis.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The Conservative Party is more evenly split between both camps and its former leader, David Cameron, supports abortion on demand in the early stages of pregnancy.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Abortion laws in the Middle East reflect variation of opinions.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Some countries permit abortion in cases involving a pregnant woman's well-being, fetal impairment, and rape.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Abortion was widely practiced during the colonial period, and allowed a longer term termination.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] By the 19th century, progressive interpretations cut the abortion time limit down to the first trimester.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] However, a 2008 World Health Organization report estimated 900,000 unsafe abortion occurred each year in the Middle Eastern and Northern Africa regions.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] While many countries have decriminalized abortions and made it more accessible, there are still a few remaining countries yet to do so.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] In April 2005, the Iranian Parliament approved a new bill easing the conditions by also allowing abortion in certain cases when the fetus shows signs of handicap.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Legal abortion is now allowed if the mother's life is in danger, and also in cases of fetal abnormalities that makes it not viable after birth (such as anencephaly) or produce difficulties for mother to take care of it after birth, such as major thalassemia or bilateral polycystic kidney disease.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Abortion-rights advocacy in the United States is centered in the United States abortion-rights movement.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Across the world, there are only four countries in which abortion is completely banned.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Honduras, Dominican Republic, Nicaragua, and El Salvador have yet to legalize abortions, even if it is for the woman's health and safety.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Since 2018, there have been no changes in the laws regarding abortion in these Latin-America countries.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The Ministry of Public Health collected data that showed nearly half the pregnancies in the Dominican Republic alone are unwanted or unplanned; often stemming from incest or rape.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Women in South America continue fighting for their rights and protection, but there has been no recent call of action.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Because Argentina has been very restrictive against abortion, reliable reporting on abortion rates is unavailable.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Argentina has long been a strongly Catholic country, and protesters seeking legalized abortion in 2013 directed anger toward the Catholic Church.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] On December 11, 2020, after a 20-hour debate, the Chamber of Deputies voted 131 to 117 (6 abstentions) to approve a bill legalizing abortion up to 14 weeks after conception.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The bill's passing resulted in large-scale celebrations by abortion rights activists who had long campaigned for it.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] The Argentine Senate approved the bill 38–29 on December 29, and it is expected to be signed by President Alberto Fernandez.
[src:gynaecology/abortion-rights-movement] Argentina will become the fourth Latin American country to legalize abortion.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] Physicians specializing in the field are in general agreement concerning applicability of treatment to those with addiction to drugs, such as alcohol and heroin, and often also to gambling, which has similar characteristics and has been well-described in the scientific literature.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] There is less agreement concerning definition or treatment of other so-called addictive behaviors such as sexual addiction and internet addiction, such behaviors not being marked generally by physiologic tolerance or withdrawal.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] Over centuries, addiction has been recognized as an issue to be treated, and has been addressed with the creation of a multitude of organizations, the passage of certain acts, and the development of various drugs in the medical field all to help those who struggle with addiction.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] Doctors focusing on addiction medicine are medical specialists who focus on addictive disease and have had special study and training focusing on the prevention and treatment of such diseases.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] There are two routes to specialization in the addiction field: one via a psychiatric pathway and one via other fields of medicine.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] The American Society of Addiction Medicine notes that approximately 40% of its members are psychiatrists (MD/DO) while the remainder have received primary medical training in other fields.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] Addiction first became well known and seen as a major issue between the 1750s and early 1800s with alcoholism running rampant and being the main contributor to this.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] Benjamin Rush first began to discern alcoholism as an illness to be addressed when he published his writing “*Inquiry into the Effects of Ardent Spirits on the Human Mind and Body*” in 1784.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] Because of his writing on alcoholism, the beginnings of the temperance movement came shortly after in the early 1800s.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] The first inebriate homes for alcoholics opened around the 1850s.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] These homes and asylums provided a segregated place for alcoholics to stay while they withdrew from the alcohol, along with integration into sobriety groups.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] Joseph Edward Turner opened the New York State Inebriate Asylum, which was the first rehabilitation center for alcoholism.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] In the late 1800s, around 1890, alcoholics were sent to hospital wards and drunk tanks as inebriate homes began shutting down.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] Throughout the first half of the 1900s, many hospitals and organizations opened to assist addicts, such as the Charles B.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] Towns substance abuse Hospital (1901), the Emmanuel Clinic/the Emmanuel movement (1906), morphine maintenance clinics (1919–1924), narcotics farms (1935), Alcoholics Anonymous (1935), etc.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] In addition to this, certain state laws were passed to try to sterilize disabled people, addicts, and people with mental disorders (1910).
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] During this time, various drugs also came out to attempt to cure alcoholism like barbiturates, amphetamines, LSD, and disulfiram (1948–1950).
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] Within these years, multiple advancements were made, certain laws or acts were passed, and more organizations came about to help people with addiction.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] In 1957, treatment units for alcoholics were developed by the Veterans Administration.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] Shortly thereafter, a multitude of associations opened.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] These include but are not limited to the Halfway House Association (1958), the Betty Ford Clinic (1982), Cocaine Anonymous (1982), Secular Organizations for Sobriety and Rational Recovery (1985–1986), and SMART Recovery (1994).
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] Along with that, drugs like methadone (1964), Narcan (1971), and naltrexone (1994) were developed to fight against opioid withdrawal and alcoholism.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] As for the legal side of things, the Controlled Substances Act passed in 1970, which classified all controlled substances into five classes, and the Drug Addiction Treatment Act passed in 1999, enforcing a stricter version of the Controlled Substances Act.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] In the past 25 years, further developments have been made in the field of addiction medicine such as the FDA approval of a treatment called buprenorphine for opioid use disorder, along with The Mental Health Parity and Addiction Equity Act (2008) and the Affordable Care Act (2010) being passed.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] The MHPAEA of 2008 made it mandatory for insurance organizations to give people coverage for the cost of substance-abuse-related treatments, while the ACA of 2010 further expanded the coverage offered for substance-abuse-related treatments through state health insurances.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] In several countries around the world, specialist bodies have been set up to ensure high quality practice in addiction medicine.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] In October 2015, the American Board of Medical Specialties (ABMS) officially recognized addiction medicine as a subspecialty.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] Within the United States, there are two accepted specialty examinations.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] One is a Board Certification in Addiction Psychiatry from the American Board of Psychiatry and Neurology.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] The other is a Board Certification in Addiction Medicine from the American Board of Preventive Medicine.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] The latter approach is available to all physicians with primary Board certification, while the former is available only to board-certified psychiatrists.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] Doctors of Osteopathic Medicine may also seek board certification via the American Osteopathic Association (AOA).
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] The Doctor of Osteopathic Medicine must have a primary board certification in Neurology & Psychiatry, Internal Medicine, or Family Practice from the American Osteopathic Association and complete an AOA approved addiction medicine fellowship.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] Successful completion of a board examination administered via the AOA will grant a certificate of added qualification (CAQ) in addiction medicine.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] Within Australia, addiction medicine specialists are certified via the Chapter of Addiction Medicine, which is part of the Royal Australasian College of Physicians.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] They may alternatively be a member of the Section of Addiction Psychiatry, Royal Australian & New Zealand College of Psychiatrists.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-medicine] The International Society of Addiction Medicine also can provide certification of expertise.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] Addiction psychiatry is a relatively new subspecialty of psychiatry.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] Years later, in 1997 the committee's board of trustees along with the ABMS renamed the committee "Committee on Certification in the Subspecialty of Addiction Psychiatry".
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] The committee became more geared toward developing the subspecialty of addiction psychiatry.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] As of 1997, there were only 13 addiction psychiatry programs that the Accreditation Council for Graduate Medical Education (ACGME) recognized.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] Currently the ACGME recognizes 45 different residency programs in the United States.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] In order to become a certified addiction psychiatrist, one must first have completed medical school and further be certified as a general psychiatrist by the ABPN.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] Next, general psychiatrists must commit themselves to an ACGME-accredited residency in addiction psychiatry.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] The addiction psychiatry residencies are one-year programs set in a hospital or clinical setting where general psychiatrists learn how to diagnose and treat substance-use disorders as well as potential coexisting psychiatric disorders.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] After completing one of these residency programs addiction psychiatrists are then capable of being hired in either a private or public setting.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] An increase in pressure from local and federal governments to provide for patients suffering from addiction has resulted in the increased demand for addiction psychiatrists.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] Federal funding for the prevention of addiction has been carried out via block grants.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] These investments in addiction treatment yield savings in overall societal costs, as general health care costs diminish.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] As of June 2018, the average reported salary of addiction psychiatrists was $250,000.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] Additionally, 47 addiction psychiatrist appeared on *U.S.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] A further 16 addiction psychiatrists were nominated by their peers to an even more selective group of America's Top Doctors.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] Addiction psychiatry aims to treat individuals with addiction issues along with co-occurring psychiatric disorders, otherwise known as patients with dual diagnosis.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] Addiction psychiatrists treat a wide variety of patients of all ages with varying conditions.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] Each case of addiction is unique and addiction psychiatrists must cater to each individual patient.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] Addiction psychiatrists must recognize the numerous factors that tie into each individual's struggle with an addiction.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] For example, substance use often occurs among individuals dealing with mood disorders and other social stresses.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] Addiction psychiatrists must be able to recognize, diagnose, and treat the disorders concurrent with the substance use issues.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] Furthermore, addiction psychiatrists must also recognize certain health effects from illicit drugs in order to properly treat each individual.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] Addiction psychiatry encompasses both medicine and psychotherapy, or professional therapeutic interaction, as the means of treating individuals.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] In a conventional addiction psychiatry session, addiction psychiatrists will gain a better understanding of their patient's lifestyle by gathering medical history and the patient's mental health concerns.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] Next, the psychiatrist will identify individualized solutions to the patient's problem; this may include medicines and/or psychotherapy.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] Addiction psychiatrists are uniquely equipped to handle co-occurring mental health diagnoses and substance use disorders (whether in the context of active use, withdrawal or early/late recovery).
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] While there are many FDA-approved medications for substance use disorder treatment, addiction psychiatrists can attune to the most appropriate medication for their specific patient.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] Acamprosate, disulfiram, and naltrexone are the most common medications used to treat alcohol use disorder.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] Buprenorphine, methadone, and naltrexone are the most common medications used to treat OUD.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] Moreover, addiction psychiatrists recommend the benefits of 12-Step programs such as Narcotics Anonymous and Alcoholics Anonymous and often encourage patients to seek external support.
[src:gynaecology/addiction-psychiatry] Addiction psychiatry can also be a method of recovery for those who have been unable to manage their substance use disorder without prior success.
[src:gynaecology/adolescent-medicine] Medicine is often categorized most simply as pediatric and adult, with the pediatric category covering from infancy through both childhood and adolescence.
[src:gynaecology/adolescent-medicine] However, such categorization is further divided in some contexts, such that adolescent medicine can be a more specific focus within pediatrics and geriatrics can be a more specific focus within adult medicine.
[src:gynaecology/adolescent-medicine] Issues with a high prevalence during adolescence are frequently addressed by providers.
[src:gynaecology/adolescent-medicine] Chronic conditions often cause delay in onset of puberty and temporary or permanent impediments to growth; conversely the growth and hormonal changes can destabilize treatment for the chronic condition.
[src:gynaecology/adolescent-medicine] An increase in independence can lead to gaps in self-management, for example, in the decreased management of diabetes.
[src:gynaecology/adolescent-medicine] In addition, issues of medical ethics, particularly related to confidentiality and the right to consent for medical care, are pertinent to the practice of adolescent medicine.
[src:gynaecology/adolescent-medicine] Marginalised young people’s healthcare journeys can be supported by advocates that help them navigate the health system.
[src:gynaecology/adolescent-medicine] The particular needs of young people when accessing healthcare have also led the WHO to publishing guidelines for adolescent-friendly health care, in an effort to increase adolescents utilization of the healthcare system.
[src:gynaecology/adolescent-medicine] Adolescent medicine providers are generally drawn from the specialties of pediatrics, internal medicine, med/peds or family medicine.
[src:gynaecology/adolescent-medicine] The **certifying boards** for these different specialties have varying requirements for certification, though all require successful completion of a fellowship and a passing score on a certifying exam.
[src:gynaecology/adolescent-medicine] The American Board of Pediatrics and the American Board of Internal Medicine require evidence of scholarly achievement by candidates for subspecialty certification, usually in the form of an original research study.
[src:gynaecology/adolescent-medicine] In the United States, the subspecialty of college health is closely affiliated with adolescent medicine.
[src:gynaecology/adolescent-medicine] Many adolescent medicine fellowships include rotations in college-based student health clinics and many adolescent medicine physicians work in college health clinics.
[src:gynaecology/adolescent-medicine] Founded in 1987, the International Association for Adolescent Health (IAAH) is a multidisciplinary, non-government organization with a broad focus on youth health.
[src:gynaecology/adolescent-medicine] In the United States, the Society for Adolescent Health and Medicine (SAHM) is the multidisciplinary, national professional association for adolescent medicine and host the most popular national adolescent medicine conference annually.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Gynaecological care is discussed in the Kahun Gynaecological Papyrus and the Hippocratic Corpus, showing the ancient origins of the subject.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Marion Sims contributed to the advancement of the specialism developing instruments such as the Sims speculum, Pantaleoni completed the first hysteroscopy in 1869 and Papanikolaou first wrote about the pap smear in 1928.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Transgender, intersex and nonbinary individuals can require gynaecological care.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Health disparities exist within gynaecology, which can impact women in low and middle income countries, minority groups in some countries and the LGBTQ+ community.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] The word *gynaecology* comes from the oblique stem (γυναικ-) of the Greek word γυνή (*gyne*) meaning 'woman', and *-logia* meaning 'study'.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Literally translated, it means 'the study of women'.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Its counterpart is andrology, which deals with medical issues specific to the male reproductive system.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] The Kahun Gynaecological Papyrus, dated to about 1800 BC, deals with gynaecological diseases, fertility, pregnancy and contraception.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] The text is divided into thirty-four parts, each dealing with a specific problem and containing diagnosis and treatment; no prognosis is suggested.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Treatments are non-surgical, consisting of applying medicines to the affected body part or delivering medicines orally.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] During this time, the womb was sometimes seen as the source of problems manifesting in other body parts.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Ayurveda, an Indian traditional medical system, also provides details about concepts and techniques related to gynaecology, addressing fertility, childbirth complications, and menstrual disorders amongst other things.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] The Hippocratic Corpus contains several gynaecological treatises dating to the 5th and 4th centuries BC.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Aristotle is another source for medical texts from the 4th century BC*.* The gynaecological treatise *Gynaikeia* by Soranus of Ephesus (1st/2nd century AD) is extant (together with a 6th-century Latin paraphrase by Muscio, a physician of the same school).
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] He was the chief representative of the school of physicians known as the "methodists".
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] During the Middle Ages, midwives dominated women's health concerns through experienced-based knowledge, traditional remedies, and herbal medicines.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Midwifery was often regarded as unscientific and was challenged with the rise of gynaecology as an official medical field.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] The Renaissance period, 16th century, brought about a resurgence of classical scientific advancements, including the rise of medical advancements in the field of gynaecology and obstetrics.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Figures like Ambroise Pare were imperative in improving obstetrics techniques during this period.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Peter Chamberlen developed the forceps, an important surgical tool that transformed childbirth and lessened maternal mortality.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] As medical institutions continued to expand in the 18th-19th centuries, the authority of midwives was challenged by men who dominated medical professions.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] The formalization of midwifery training by male doctors and advancements in medical knowledge of women's health and anatomy occurred during this period.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Figures such as William Smellie, William Hunter, Paul Zweifel, Franz Karl Naegele, and Carl Crede contributed to the understanding of childbirth and women's health in Europe.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] In the early 18th and 19th centuries, in the United States, the field of gyneacology, as with most medical specialities, had ties to black women and therefore slavery.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Brothers Henry and Robert Campbell were editors of the first medical journal in the deep south.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Henry worked as gynaecologist including on enslaved women, whilst publishing medical case narratives of operations in the journal the brothers edited.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Mary Putnam Jacobi, challenged the exclusion of women from medical education and shifted gynaecology to a scientific practice.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Marion Sims is regarded as the father of modern gynaecology.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Some of his published medical contributions included the development of the Sims' position (1845), the Sims' speculum (1845), the Sims' sigmoid catheter, and gynaecological surgery.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] He was the first to develop surgical techniques for the repair of vesico-vaginal fistulas (1849), a consequence of protracted childbirth which at the time was without treatment.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] He founded the first women's hospital in the country in Alabama 1855 and subsequently the Woman's Hospital of New York in 1857.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] He was elected president of the American Medical Association in 1876.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Sims conducted experimental operations on black enslaved women, without anaesthesia.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Historically, white women were also subjected to experimental medical procedures.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] In terms of common procedures within gynaecology, the first hysteroscopy was completed in 1869 by Pantaleoni, to treat an endometrial polyp, using a cystoscope.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Obstetrics and gynaecology were recognized as specialties in the mid-19th century, in the United Kingdom.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Specialist societies came into being but it became clear that to become disciplines in their own right, a separate college was required.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Georgios Papanikaou, from Greece, is credited with discovering the pap smear test, he identified differences in the cytology of normal and malignant cervical cells by viewing swabs smeared on microscopic slides.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] His first publication of the finding in 1928 was not widely received.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] He later collaborated with Dr Herbert Traut at an American hospital and they published a book, Diagnosis of Uterine Cancer by the Vaginal Smear and this medical advancement became more widely known about.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] By the 20th century, the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (1951) was founded.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] There were advances in antiseptic techniques, anaesthesia, and diagnostic tools, which transformed gynaecological care.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Minority groups in the United States experienced forced sterilizations and eugenic policies.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Between 1909 and 1979, an estimated 20,000 forced sterilizations occurred in California, primarily in mental institutions and prisons.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Healthcare later became more focused on the importance of informed consent.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] In Canada during the 1940's, practitioners focused on obstetrics and gynaecology began identifying the need for a separate organization to deal with this specialism and the idea to form the Society of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists of Canada (SOGC) was conceived.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] The Royal College of Physicians and Surgeons formally recognized obstetrics & gynaecology in 1957.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Ian Donald, a gynaecologist from the United Kingdom was an early pioneer of the use of sonography within gyneacology and obstetrics.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] He gained knowledge of radar technology in the air force and working with an engineer called Tom Brown and an engineering company, they developed a compact 2D ultrasound machine.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] In 1958, he published a paper in the Lancet.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Newer techniques for hysterectomies have evolved over time, with the first laparoscopic hysterectomy completed by Harry Reich in Pennsylvania, in January 1988.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Margaret Sanger worked to make contraception legal and available.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] In 1951 she met Gregory Pincus and in a project that was financially sponsored by Katharine McCormick, they developed the contraceptive pill.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] In 1954, due to anti-birth control laws, the first trials in Massachusetts were positioned as being fertility trials.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Gregory Pincus and John Rock conducted these trials.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Oral progesterone was tested on fertility patients, with consent, however the oral contraceptive was also tested on 28 psychiatric patients at Worcester State Hospital, without the patients consent.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] They discovered that women stopped ovulating and that this occurred only whilst taking this.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] To get FDA approval, a larger clinical trial was needed.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Larger clinical trials took place in Puerto Rico, a territory of the United States.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Puerto Rico had no anti-birth control laws and already had services offering birth control.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Trials began in Rio Piedras in 1956, and women were offered the pill, called Envoid in 1960, on the basis it prevented pregnancy, without knowing it did not have FDA approval.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Three women died in the trial and criticisms include that side effects were not taken seriously.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Edris Rice-Wray, a professor at the Puerto Rico Medical School raised concerns about the negative side effects of the pill.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] In some countries or within some healthcare systems, women must first see a general practitioner or family practitioner before seeing a gynaecologist.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] If the condition cannot be diagnosed or treated and requires a specialist the patient is referred to a gynaecologist.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] In other countries, patients can see a gynaecologist without a referral.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Gynecologists give reproductive and sexual health services that include pelvic exams, Pap tests, cancer screenings, treatment for hormone imbalance, and testing and treatment for vaginal infections.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] They diagnose and treat reproductive system disorders such as endometriosis, infertility, ovarian cysts, and pelvic pain.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] They may also care for people with ovarian, cervical, and other reproductive cancers.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] As with all of medicine, the main tools of diagnosis are clinical history, examination and investigations.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Gynaecological examination is quite intimate, more so than a routine physical exam.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] It can also require instruments such as the speculum which is used to retract the tissues of the vagina to allow examination of the cervix, the lower part of the uterus located within the upper portion of the vagina.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Gynaecologists may do a bimanual examination (one hand on the abdomen and one or two fingers in the vagina) to palpate the cervix, uterus, ovaries and pelvis.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] An abdominal or vaginal ultrasound can be used for diagnostic purposes.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] This can help to detect growths, such as polyps, endometrial hyperplasia, carcinoma, endometriosis, pelvic inflammatory disease, polycystic ovary syndrome and many other gynaecology conditions.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] This is a very common diagnostic technique.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Hormone tests can be useful when investigating gynaecology based conditions or symptoms.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] These may check the hormone levels of oestradiol, progesterone, follicle stimulating hormone and luteinizing hormones, for example.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Levels considered not normal, could indicate the presence of conditions and could impact reproductive function.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Some of these conditions are dealt with by doctors with specialisms other than, or in addition to, gynaecology.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] For example, a woman with urinary incontinence may be referred to a doctor with urology specialist experience and someone with cancer may be treated by a multidisciplinary team with specialist oncology experience.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Gynaecologists may use medical and/or surgical treatments, depending on the medical condition they are treating.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Pre- and post-operative medical management often utilises drug therapies, such as antibiotics, diuretics, antihypertensives, and antiemetics.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Additionally, gynaecologists make frequent use of specialized hormone-modulating therapies (such as Clomifene citrate and hormonal contraception) to treat disorders of the female genital tract that are responsive to pituitary or gonadal signals.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Surgery can be used to treat gynaecology conditions.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] In the past, gynaecologists were not considered "surgeons", although this is the source of controversy.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Modern advancements in general surgery and gynaecology, mean there is now less of a distinction.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] The rise of sub-specialties within gynaecology which are primarily surgical in nature (for example urogynaecology and gynaecological oncology) have strengthened the reputations of gynaecologists as surgical practitioners.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Gynaecologists are now eligible for fellowship in both the American College of Surgeons and Royal Colleges of Surgeons, and many newer surgical textbooks include chapters on (at least basic) gynaecological surgery.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Endometrial ablation (destroys layer of the endometrium to reduce bleeding).
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Tubal ligation (a type of permanent sterilization).
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Hysteroscopy (inspection of the uterine cavity) – Hysteroscopy can be used to minimally invasive remove uterine fibroids, and in some cases a diode laser may be employed for precise excision.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] This approach minimizes tissue damage and bleeding, reduces the risk of adhesions, and may be suitable for patients wishing to preserve fertility.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Laparoscopy – minimally invasive surgery used to diagnose or treat a variety of conditions.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] It can be used to treat uterine fibroids and accurately diagnose and treat pelvic/abdominal endometriosis.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Endometriotic lesions may be excised or ablated using heat, including laser, preserving surrounding tissue and anatomy, reducing scars and adhesions, and supporting fertility.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Laparotomy – may be used to investigate the level of progression of benign or malignant disease, or to assess and repair damage to the pelvic organs.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Various surgical treatments for urinary incontinence and pelvic prolapse, including mid-urethral mesh sling procedures.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Appendectomy – often performed to remove site of painful endometriosis implantation or prophylactically (against future acute appendicitis) at the time of hysterectomy or Caesarean section.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] May also be performed as part of a staging operation for ovarian cancer.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Cervical Excision Procedures (including cryosurgery) – removal of the surface of the cervix containing pre-cancerous cells which have been previously identified on Pap smear.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Non-invasive as well as non-hormonal laser treatment for atrophic vaginitis.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Tranexamic acid has been found to be an effective drug to reduce the amount of bleeding during menstruation and medical procedures, so can be used to treat menorrhagia.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Hormone based IUDs, such as Mirena have also been shown to help reduce heavy periods.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Organizations such as the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) advocate such treatments before surgical intervention, but studies reveal many women who had a hysterectomy between 2011 and 2019 did not receive any other treatments before this.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Hormonal therapy can be used as a non-surgical treatment for endometriosis.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Research shows gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) antagonists, like elagolix, can give encouraging results in managing some symptoms.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Also encouraging is research on aromatase inhibitors, such as letrozole that has shown efficacy in reducing lesion size and pain severity.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Some transgender women prefer to see gynaecologists for relevant routine health checks.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Transgender men may also seek care from gynaecologists as they may not have undertook sex reassignment and still require routine health checks.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Gynaecologists often play an important role in the surgical team that helps female to male transsexuals.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Newer advancements in gynaecology include the integration of artificial intelligence (AI) in clinical practice, specifically with diagnostics and predictive analytics.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] AI algorithms are able to interpret complex gynaecological imaging and pathology data, which improves diagnostic accuracy.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] These technologies are especially used in identifying cervical and ovarian cancers and predicting treatment outcomes.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Liquid biopsy is emerging as an important noninvasive tool to detect and monitor gynaecology cancers.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Tumour-derived biomarkers, such as circulating tumour DNA (ctDNA), circulating tumour cells (CTCs), exosomes and microRNA, can provide insights into the biological behaviour of gynaecology cancers.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Some believe this could revolutionize cancer treatment, assisting with earlier detection and predicting disease recurrence.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] In terms of surgery, research has led to minimally invasive approaches, such as vaginal natural orifice transluminal endoscopic surgery.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] This technique allows surgeons to access the pelvic cavity through the vaginal canal, reducing recovery times, postoperative pain, and complication rates in comparison to traditional methods.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Globally, there have been efforts to decrease variations in gynaecology curriculums, at undergraduate and postgraduate levels, between different countries and universities.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] An example of this is FIGO's international recommendations of the core competencies required to become a gynaecologist.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Some postgraduate/residency training has moved from being duration based, to being competency based.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] At undergraduate and postgraduate levels, simulations (such as virtual reality laparoscopic simulators) form an important part of training, so skills can be developed before (and whilst) training working with patients.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Postgraduate training globally differs by length of training, cases studied and by oversight.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Due to advancements in treatments, qualified gynaecologists must continuously obtain new skills and knowledge.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] In some jurisdictions it is a requirement for gynaecologists to gain continuing medical education credits (annually or biannually).
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] In the United States, obstetrics and gynaecology typically requires residency training for four years.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] This encompasses comprehensive clinical and surgical education.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] OBGYN residents participate in a yearly in-training exam that is administered by the Council on Resident Education in Obstetrics and Gynecology (CREOG).
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Research suggests that combining curriculum and focused mentorship can improve residents' performance on the exam and overall educational outcomes.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] In the United Kingdom, the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists, based in London, encourages the study and advancement of both the science and practice of obstetrics and gynaecology.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] This is done through postgraduate medical education and training development, and the publication of clinical guidelines and reports on aspects of the specialty and service provision.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] The RCOG International Office works with other international organizations to help lower maternal morbidity and mortality in under-resourced countries.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Gynaecologic oncology is a subspecialty of gynaecology, dealing with gynaecology-related cancer.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] To become a gynaecology oncologist requires specialist further training.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Urogynaecology is also a subspecialty of gynaecology and urology.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Further fellowship training is needed to become a urogynaecologist.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] It is recommended that all gynaecologists study gynaecologic oncology and urogynaecology, to develop core competencies relevant to these fields.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Improved access to education and the professions in recent decades has seen women gynaecologists outnumber men in the once male-dominated medical field of gynaecology.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] In some gynaecological sub-specialties, where an over-representation of males persists, income discrepancies appear to show male practitioners earning higher averages.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Surveys of women's views on the issue of male doctors conducting intimate examinations show a large and consistent majority found it uncomfortable, were more likely to be embarrassed and less likely to talk openly or in detail about personal information, or discuss their sexual history with a man.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] The findings raised questions about the ability of male gynaecologists to offer quality care to patients.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] This, when coupled with more women choosing female physicians has decreased the employment opportunities for men choosing to become gynaecologists.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] According to one source, "there is a sharp decline in the number of men opting for OB/GYN residency programs and general OB/GYN programs due to the sexist market trends.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] In the United States, it has been reported that four in five students choosing a residency in gynaecology are now female.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] In several places in Sweden, to comply with discrimination laws, patients may not choose a doctor—regardless of specialty—based on factors such as gender and declining to see a doctor because of their gender may legally be viewed as refusing care.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] In Turkey, due to patient preference to be seen by another female, there are now few male gynaecologists working in the field.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] There have been a number of legal challenges in the US against healthcare providers who have started hiring based on the gender of physicians.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Mircea Veleanu argued, in part, that his former employers discriminated against him by accommodating the wishes of female patients who had requested female doctors for intimate exams.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] A male nurse complained about an advert for an all-female obstetrics and gynaecology practice in Columbia, Maryland, claiming this was a form of sexual discrimination.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] In 2000, David Garfinkel, a New Jersey-based OB-GYN, sued his former employer after being fired due to, as he claimed, "because I was male, I wasn't drawing as many patients as they'd expected".
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Subsequent to research, some organizations such as the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists have called on global governments and international health bodies to address the impact of benign gynaecology conditions in low and middle income countries.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] They found the years lost to disability from these conditions was greater than combined morbidity from malaria, TB and HIV/AIDS, accounting for 8% of all years lost to disability, for women aged 15–49.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] They argue that such conditions are neglected within the global health arena and have a significant impact on women in low and middle income countries.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Some benign and common gynaecology conditions have been found to disproportionately impact certain racial and ethnic groups.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] One study found that black women are three times more likely than white women, to have uterine fibroids, a variety of studies found they are more likely to get these at a younger age and are more likely to have numerous and rapid growing fibroids.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] This may be due to biological, lifestyle, environmental and clinical factors, further research is needed to understand why this disparity exists.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] In regards to endometriosis, some research suggests this disproportionately impacts asian women, with black and hispanic women less likely to have this condition.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Research about this is somewhat inconsistent suggesting further studies would be beneficial.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] In the United States, health disparities persist in gynaecology, disproportionately affecting women of colour, low-income women, and those living in rural areas.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Black women face higher rates of mortality from some gynaecology based cancers.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] The reasons for these disparities is complex and involves racial, economic, educational and geographic factors that influence treatment and survival.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Importantly, a variation from evidenced-based treatment has been indicated as a modifiable factor that can effect survival outcomes.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] This problem disproportionately impacts black women and poorer women.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] These disparities are compounded by barriers such as lack of insurance and best practice not being followed, particularly when funded by Medicaid.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Some research in the United States shows that hispanic women had a more favourable prognosis compared to non-hispanic women, in regards to certain gynaecology based cancers.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] With ovarian cancer black women tended to present with more advanced ovarian cancer compared to white women, so were diagnosed at a later stage.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] The incidence rates of endometrial and ovarian cancer was highest in white women and the incidence of cervical cancer was highest in black women.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Research showed that black and hispanic women were less likely to complete the full number of HPV vaccinations, the cause of some gynaecology based cancers.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Marginalized groups are less likely to have their pain and symptoms taken seriously by providers, leading to delayed diagnoses and worse outcomes.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Addressing these disparities requires having physicians practice cultural humility and physician's addressing their possible bias.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Research from the United States shows that disabled women are screened less for cervical cancer and less likely to have pelvic examinations.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] They report lower levels of receiving family planning services.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Health service usage and whether or not they have insurance did not explain differences in screening levels.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Research showed they were less likely to receive doctors recommendations.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Women with disabilities also have a greater chance of dying from cervical cancer in counties such as South Korea and Sweden.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] In the United Kingdom, in regards to ovarian cancer socioeconomic factors appear to create a disparity in treatment and outcomes.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Delays and treatment inequalities may contribute to worse outcomes for women from more deprived areas, with them less likely to receive surgery or chemotherapy.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] How wealthy a woman is, directly impacted mortality rates.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Cervical screening attendance, which helps to diagnose cervical cancer at an early stage has declined, particularly among minority ethnic groups and in more deprived areas.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Medical bias in doctor and patient interactions can cause delays to diagnosis and can stem from subconscious stereotypes, in relation to ethnicity or socioeconomic status.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] The LGBTQ+ community also face health disparities within gyneacology care.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Nearly one in five lesbian and bisexual women have never attended cervical screening.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Transexual men and non binary people with a cervix are also less likely to access cervical screening.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Research has shown that 22.8% of transgender people avoid accessing healthcare due to anticipated discrimination.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Gyneacologists play an important role in caring for transgender patients, who face barriers within health care, as a result of marginalization and discrimination.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Indigenous women in Australia are more likely to die from gynaecology cancers.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Research suggests that strategies to reduce survival disparities should target earlier diagnosis and earlier treatment, as aboriginal women were more likely to present with more advanced cancer at the point of diagnosis and decline treatment.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] Research in Australia examined the issue of pelvic floor dysfunction in aboriginal women, in New South Wales.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] This showed a high burden of disease and that there was a reluctance of these women to seek care, due to fear of judgement and embarrassment.
[src:gynaecology/gynaecology] The authors concluded that culturally appropriate and tailored care was needed to tackle this.
